{"title_page": "Kim Yo-jong", "text_new": "{{pp-blp|small=yes}}\n<!-- As of April 20th, 2020, there has been no official announcement as to whether or not Kim Yo-jong has succeeded Kim Jong-un as Supreme Leader of North Korea. -->\n{{short description|Younger sister of North Korean leader Kim Jong-un}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2018}}\n{{Korean name|Kim}}\n{{Infobox officeholder \n| name        = Kim Yo-jong\n| image       = Kim Yo-jong at Blue House (cropped).jpg\n| image_size   = 220px \n|office = First Deputy Director of the [[Propaganda and Agitation Department]]\n|term_start = November 2014\n|2blankname = Director\n|2namedata = [[Kim Ki-nam]]<br>[[Pak Kwang-ho]]<br>[[Ri Il-hwan]]\n|predecessor = ''Office established''\n| 1blankname = {{nowrap|[[Supreme Leader of North Korea|Supreme Leader]]}}\n| 1namedata = [[Kim Jong-un]]\n| alt         = \n| caption     = Kim Yo-jong in February 2018\n| birth_name  = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1988|9|26|}}\n| birth_place = [[Pyongyang]], [[North Korea]]\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = [[North Korea]]n\n| other_names = \n| occupation  = \n| known_for   = \n| alma_mater  = [[Kim Il-sung Military University]]\n| parents     = [[Kim Jong-il]]<br />[[Ko Yong-hui]]\n| signature   = Signature of Kim Yo-jong.svg\n| signature_alt   = Signature of Kim Yo-jong\n| module      = {{Infobox Korean name|child=yes\n| hangul  = \uae40\uc5ec\uc815\n| hanja   = {{linktext|lang=ko-Hant|\u91d1|\u8207|\u6b63}}\n| rr      = Gim Yeojeong\n| mr      = Kim Y\u014fj\u014fng\n| context = north}}\n}}\n\n'''Kim Yo-jong''' ({{lang-ko|\uae40\uc5ec\uc815}}, born 26 September 1988)<ref>{{cite news |script-title=ko:\ud1b5\uc77c\ubd80, \uae40\uc5ec\uc815 '1988\ub144\uc0dd' \uacf5\uc2dd \ud310\ub2e8\u2026\uc791\ub144\uc5d4 '\uc5f0\ub3c4\ubbf8\uc0c1' \ud45c\uae30 |url=http://news.mk.co.kr/newsRead.php?year=2018&no=806316 |accessdate=4 January 2019 |work=MK News |date=27 December 2018 |language=Korean}}</ref><ref name=leaderwatch>{{cite news|url=http://nkleadershipwatch.wordpress.com/kim-family/kim-yo-jong/|title=Kim Yo Jong|publisher=North Korea Leadership Watch|date=6 May 2016|access-date=18 December 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190213133651/https://nkleadershipwatch.wordpress.com/kim-family/kim-yo-jong/|archive-date=13 February 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref> is a North Korean politician. She is the youngest daughter of former supreme leader [[Kim Jong-il]]. Her brother is [[Kim Jong-un]], the current supreme leader. She is an alternate member of the [[Politburo of the Workers' Party of Korea|Politburo]] (Political Bureau) and vice director of the [[Propaganda and Agitation Department]] of the [[Workers' Party of Korea]] (WPK).\n\n==Early life==\nKim Yo-jong was born to [[Kim Jong-il]] and his wife [[Ko Yong-hui]] on 26 September 1988.<ref name=leaderwatch/> She and her brother, Kim Jong-un, are said to have a close relationship,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dw.com/en/kim-yo-jong-who-is-the-north-korean-leaders-mysterious-sister/a-40862677|title=Kim Yo Jong: Who is the North Korean leader's mysterious sister? {{!}} News {{!}} DW {{!}} 8 October 2017|last=(www.dw.com)|first=Deutsche Welle|website=DW.COM|language=en|access-date=9 October 2017}}</ref> due to shared isolated years while studying together in [[Switzerland]] from 1996 to 2000, and in North Korea, \"where social and emotional isolation appears to have been a defining force in their early lives\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.38north.org/2015/08/mmadden081415/|title=North Korea\u2019s New Propagandist?|date=14 August 2015|work=38 North|access-date=9 October 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> possibly because their father Kim Jong-Il wanted to bring them up away from the influence of his father [[Kim Il-sung]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.newsweek.com/who-kim-yo-jong-kim-jong-un-sister-becoming-north-korea-most-powerful-woman-802439|title=Who is Kim Jong Un\u2019s sister? Kim Jo Yong is becoming North Korea\u2019s most powerful woman|last=O'Connor|first=Tom|date=9 February 2018|work=Newsweek|access-date=10 February 2018|language=en}}</ref> She may have studied at the [[Kim Il-sung Military University]] after her return.<ref name=leaderwatch/> She also studied computer science at [[Kim Il-sung University]] where she is said to have studied with [[Kim Eun-gyong]], the daughter of [[North Korean abductions of Japanese citizens|Japanese abductee]] [[Megumi Yokota]].<ref name=\"kore_Abdu\">{{Cite web | title = Abductee\u2019s daughter is favorite of Kim\u2019s sister | author = Kim Hee-Jin | work = [[Korea JoongAng Daily]] | date = 19 March 2014 | accessdate = 30 April 2015 | url = http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=2986592 }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nKim's first public appearance was at a photo session for participants at the {{ill|3rd Conference of the Workers' Party of Korea|ko|\uc870\uc120\ub85c\ub3d9\ub2f9 \uc81c3\ucc28 \ub300\ud45c\uc790\ud68c|lt=3rd Conference of the WPK}} in September 2010, when she stood next to her father's personal secretary and alleged mistress [[Kim Ok]].<ref name=\"kji-youngest\">{{cite news|location=South Korea|url=http://nkleadershipwatch.wordpress.com/2013/07/22/kji-youngest-daughter-working-as-events-manager-for-kju/|title=KJI Youngest Daughter Working as Events Manager for KJU?|work=North Korea Leadership Watch|date=22 July 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131222045126/http://nkleadershipwatch.wordpress.com/2013/07/22/kji-youngest-daughter-working-as-events-manager-for-kju/|archivedate=22 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nKim Yo-jong was given much publicity during the funeral service for Kim Jong-il in December 2011, when she appeared several times alongside her brother Kim Jong-un or leading funeral processions of central officials, despite not even being a funeral committee member, and she was never named. She was then reportedly given a position under the [[National Defence Commission]] at the beginning of 2012 as tour manager for Kim Jong-un,<ref>{{cite news |location=South Korea |url=http://www.hani.co.kr/arti/english_edition/e_northkorea/596633.html/ |title=Kim Yo-jung is believed to have studied abroad and to share her older brother\u2019s ambition |publisher=Hankyoreh|date=22 July 2013}}</ref> but has not appeared in news reports except for November 2012, when the [[Korean Central Television]] showed her accompanying Kim Jong-un at a military riding ground.<ref>{{cite news |location=South Korea |url= http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/search1/2603000000.html?cid=AEN20121121007000325 |title=North Korea Newsletter No. 237 |publisher=Yonhap News Agency |date=22 November 2013}}</ref> She was officially mentioned for the first time on 9 March 2014, as she accompanied her brother in voting for the [[Supreme People's Assembly]]. Kim Yo-jong was identified as a \"senior official\" of the [[Central Committee of the Workers' Party of Korea|WPK Central Committee]].<ref>{{cite news|location=North Korea (site in Japan) |url=http://www.kcna.co.jp/item/2014/201403/news09/20140309-19ee.html |title=Kim Jong Un Visits Kim Il Sung University of Politics and Takes Part in Election of Deputy to SPA |publisher=Korean Central News Agency |date=9 March 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140310111435/http://www.kcna.co.jp/item/2014/201403/news09/20140309-19ee.html |archivedate=10 March 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn October 2014, she was reported to have possibly taken over state duties for her ailing brother while he underwent medical treatment.<ref>{{Cite web |url= http://www.ibtimes.com/has-kim-yo-jong-taken-over-kim-jong-un-sister-assumes-north-korea-state-duties-while-1698550 |title=Has Kim Yo-Jong Taken Over For Kim Jong Un? Sister Assumes North Korea State Duties While Brother Undergoes Medical Treatment |date=2 October 2014|accessdate=3 October 2014|work=International Business Times|last=Silva |first=Cristina}}</ref>\n\n[[File:President Moon in PyeongChang 2018 opening ceremony-02.jpg|thumb|Kim Yo-jong, [[President of South Korea|South Korean President]] [[Moon Jae-in]] and [[Vice President of the United States|U.S. Vice President]] [[Mike Pence]] at the [[2018 Winter Olympics opening ceremony]]]]\nIn November 2014, she was reported to be Vice Director of the Workers Party's [[Propaganda and Agitation Department]] (PAD).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/11/28/us-northkorea-politics-kim-idUSKCN0JC04A20141128|title=North Korea's 'princess' moves closer to center of power|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151126100412/http://www.reuters.com/article/2014/11/30/us-northkorea-politics-kim-idUSKCN0JC04A20141130|archive-date=26 November 2015|date=29 November 2014|last1=Pearson|first1=James|author2=Ju-min Park|agency=Reuters}}</ref> In July 2015, reports saw her as playing the role of ''de facto'' leader of the department, with nominal director [[Kim Ki-nam]] in a supporting role.<ref>{{cite news |location=UK |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/jul/24/kim-jong-un-sister-promoted-north-korea |title=Kim Jong-un's sister promoted to run 'idolisation projects' in North Korea |work=The Guardian |date=24 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | title = Kim Yo Jong in de facto power of PAD | author = Lee Sang Yong | work = Daily NK | date = 20 July 2015 | accessdate = 28 May 2018 | url = http://english.dailynk.com/english/read.php?num=13352&cataId=nk01500 }}</ref> She also holds a vice-ministerial post, but her portfolio is not known.<ref name=\"engl_TheC\"/> She regularly accompanies Kim Jong-un on his \"field guidance\" trips.<ref name=afp>{{cite web |url=https://news.yahoo.com/n-koreas-kim-jong-un-executed-15-top-090014485.html |title=N. Korea's Kim Jong-un executed 15 top officials: S. Korea spy agency |work=Yahoo! News|agency=AFP |date=29 April 2015|accessdate=29 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[File:2018 inter-Korean summit 02.jpg|thumb|Talks inside the [[Peace House]] in April 2018]]\nShe has been said to be the driving force behind the development of her brother's [[North Korean cult of personality|cult of personality]], modelled after that of their grandfather, [[Kim Il-sung]].<ref name=\":0\" /> This would help explain changes in the way state policies are depicted in the media, as well as differences in reporting.<ref name=\":0\" /> [[Thae Yong-ho]], a North Korean defector and former diplomat, said in 2017 that Kim Yo-jong organised all major public events in North Korea. Kim Yo-jong was said to have encouraged her brother to present an image of a \"man of the people\" with, for example, rides on fairground attractions and his friendship with the basketball star [[Dennis Rodman]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/sister-helps-kim-strut-his-stuff-as-key-missile-test-looms-jjf8gdvzk|title=Sister helps Kim strut his stuff as key missile test looms|last=Sherwell|first=Phillip|date=8 January 2017|newspaper=The Times|access-date=15 February 2017|work=|language=en|url-access=registration |via=}}</ref><ref name=\"Justin\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/oct/09/kim-yo-jong-sister-brains-behind-kim-jong-uns-image|title=Meet Kim Yo-jong, the sister who is the brains behind Kim Jong-un's image|last=McCurry|first=Justin|date=9 October 2017|work=The Guardian|access-date=8 January 2018|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2017, she was placed on the [[United States Department of the Treasury|US Treasury]]'s [[Specially Designated Nationals List]] in response to human rights abuses in North Korea.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-northkorea-sanctions/u-s-slaps-sanctions-on-seven-north-koreans-two-dprk-entities-idUSKBN14V2HS|title=U.S. blacklists North Korean officials over rights abuses|date= 11 January 2017|work=Reuters|access-date=9 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Kim Yo-jong was made an alternate member of the [[Politburo of the Workers' Party of Korea|politburo]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-northkorea-missiles-kim/kim-jong-un-praises-nuclear-program-promotes-sister-to-center-of-power-idUSKBN1CD03V|title=Kim Jong Un praises nuclear program, promotes sister to center of power|publisher=Reuters|date=8 October 2017}}</ref> only the second woman to be appointed to this decision-making body.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/kims-sister-act-the-rapid-ascent-of-north-koreas-new-top-aide-1518181299|title=Behind the Rapid Rise of Kim Jong Un\u2019s Younger Sister|last=Gale|first=Alastair|date=9 February 2018|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=10 February 2018|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> As it was previously speculated,<ref>{{cite news |location=United Kingdom |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/northkorea/10499642/Kim-Jong-un-preparing-to-purge-aunt.html |title=Kim Jong-un 'preparing to purge aunt' |work=The Telegraph |date=6 December 2013}}</ref> her ascension to the country's supreme governing body may indicate that she is Kim Jong-un\u2019s replacement for his aunt, [[Kim Kyong-hui]] (with whom Kim Yo-jong is said to have a good relationship),<ref name=kji-youngest/> who has not played an active role in his regime.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/oct/09/kim-yo-jong-sister-brains-behind-kim-jong-uns-image|title=Meet Kim Yo-jong, the sister who is the brains behind Kim Jong-un's image|last=McCurry|first=Justin|date=9 October 2017|work=The Guardian|access-date=9 October 2017|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> It has also been hinted that her newly assigned position would also put her in charge of the [[State Security Department]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2018/01/25/2018012501295.html#top|title=Kim Jong-un 'Puts Sister in Charge of State Security'|access-date=30 January 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 February 2018, Yo-jong attended the [[2018 Winter Olympics opening ceremony]] in [[Pyeongchang]], South Korea. This was the first time that a member of the ruling [[Kim dynasty (North Korea)|Kim dynasty]] had visited South Korea since the [[Korean War]].<ref name=\"theg_USvi\">{{Cite web | title = US vice-president skips Olympics dinner in snub to North Korea officials | last = Haas | first = Benjamin | work = the Guardian | date = 9 February 2018 | access-date = 9 February 2018 | url = https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/feb/09/kim-jong-uns-sister-arrives-in-south-korea-for-winter-olympics}}</ref> She attended the meeting with [[President of South Korea|South Korean President]] [[Moon Jae-in]] on 10 February, and revealed she was dispatched as a special envoy of Kim Jong-un and delivered a personally written letter from Kim to Moon.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/nation/2018/02/103_243936.html|title=South Korean president invited to North Korea|date=10 February 2018|work=koreatimes|access-date=11 February 2018|language=en}}</ref> Kim was later part of her brother's team during the [[2018 North Korea\u2013United States Singapore Summit]]<ref>https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/kim-jong-un-meets-pm-lee-ahead-of-trump-kim-summit-10414948</ref> and the [[2019 North Korea\u2013United States Hanoi Summit]]. Her involvement in diplomatic affairs continued as she issued an official statement in March 2020 from her capacity as first deputy department director of the party.<ref name=\"statement\">{{Cite web | title = Kim Jong Un sister's first official remarks hint at higher status |\n work = Al Jazeera | date = 3 March 2020 | accessdate = 13 April 2020 | url = https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/kim-jong-sister-official-remarks-hint-higher-status-200304024330626.html }}</ref>\n\nAccording to Kim Yong-hyun, a professor of North Korean studies at Dongguk University in Seoul, and others, the promotion of  Kim Yo-jong and others is a sign that \"the Kim Jong-un regime has ended its co-existence with the remnants of the previous Kim Jong-il regime by carrying out a generational replacement in the party\u2019s key elite posts\".<ref name=\"Justin\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-5205399/Kim-Jong-uns-sister-sits-yards-promotion.html|title=Kim Jong-un's sister sits just yards from the tyrant after promotion|work=Mail Online|access-date=8 January 2018}}</ref> ''Newsweek''{{'}}s Tom O'Connor echoed this opinion, writing that Kim Yo-jong's rise to power was part of Kim Jong-un's overall plan to appoint younger people in place of his father's older elites who may have harboured doubts about the younger Kim Jong-un's ability to lead North Korea.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nKim was elected to the [[Supreme People's Assembly]] during the [[2019 North Korean parliamentary election]],<ref name=NorthKoreaElection>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/amp/world-asia-47535658|title=North Korea election: Surprise as leader Kim Jong-un 'not on ballot|work=BBC News|access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> representing [[Killimgil]].<ref>{{Cite web |script-title=ko:\ubd81 \uae40\uc815\uc740, \ucd5c\uace0\uc778\ubbfc\ud68c\uc758 \ub300\uc758\uc6d0 \ucc98\uc74c \ube60\uc838: (\ucd94\uac00) \ubd81 \uc5b8\ub860, 687\uba85 \ub300\uc758\uc6d0 \uba85\ub2e8 \ubc1c\ud45c...\ub2f9 \ubd80\uc704\uc6d0\uc7a5\ub4e4 \ud3ec\ud568 (\uba85\ub2e8) |author=Jo Jung-hoon |work=Tongil News |date=12 March 2019 |access-date=18 March 2019 |url= http://www.tongilnews.com/news/articleView.html?idxno=128110 |language=ko  }}</ref> In April of the same year, she was briefly removed from the party politburo, before being reinstated in April 2020.<ref name=KYJreinstated>{{Cite news|url=https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20200412000553325|title=(3rd LD) N.K. leader holds politburo meeting to discuss anti-virus measures\n|work=Yonhap|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref> On April 21, 2020, rumors of Kim Jong-un's death has pushed Kim Yo-Jong into focus as the possible successor of the government's leadership in North Korea.<ref name=KYJleader>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newsweek.com/who-kim-jong-uns-sister-north-korea-leaders-reported-health-problems-push-kim-yo-jong-focus-1499135|title=WHO IS KIM JONG UN'S SISTER? NORTH KOREA LEADER'S REPORTED HEALTH PROBLEMS PUSH KIM YO JONG INTO FOCUS|work=DAVID BRENNAN |access-date=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn January 2015, she reportedly married Choe Song,<ref>(2 January 2015) [https://blogs.wsj.com/korearealtime/2015/01/02/kim-jong-uns-little-sister-married-son-of-top-regime-official-report-says/ Kim Jong Un\u2019s Little Sister Married Son of Top Regime Official, Report Says] Wall Street Journal, Asia, Retrieved 16 January 2015</ref> the second son of government official [[Choe Ryong-hae]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/northkorea/2015/01/02/97/0401000000AEN20150102006900315F.html|title=NK leader's sister weds son of Choe Ryong-hae: sources|publisher=Yonhap News Agency}}</ref> However, South Korean government sources have disputed the accuracy of these reports.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}} Kim Yo-jong was expecting a child in May 2015. The father, not identified, is thought to be a fellow alumnus of Kim Il-sung university and either an official at [[Room 39]] of the [[Workers' Party of Korea]] (WPK) or working at a military unit responsible for guarding the country's leader.<ref name=\"engl_TheC\">{{Cite web | title = The Chosun Ilbo (English Edition): Daily News from Korea \u2013 Kim Jong-un's Sister to Have Baby in May | work = [[Chosun Ilbo]] | date = 30 April 2014 | accessdate = 30 April 2014 | url = http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2015/04/30/2015043001119.html }}</ref>\n{{Kim Jong-il family}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|North Korea|Biography|Politics}}\n*[[Kim Kyong-hui]]\n*[[Kim Song-hye]]\n*[[Kim Sol-song]]\n*[[Politics of North Korea]]\n*[[Ro Song-sil]]\n*[[Women in North Korea]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Commons category-inline}}\n\n{{Family of Kim Jong-il}}\n{{Women in North Korean politics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kim, Yo-jong}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Kim dynasty (North Korea)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Supreme People's Assembly]]\n[[Category:North Korean women in politics]]\n[[Category:Workers' Party of Korea politicians]]\n[[Category:Kim Il-sung University alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Pyongyang]]\n[[Category:North Korean people of Japanese descent]]\n[[Category:North Korean politicians of Japanese descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-blp|small=yes}}\n<!-- As of April 20th, 2020, there has been no official announcement as to whether or not Kim Yo-jong has succeeded Kim Jong-un as Supreme Leader of North Korea. -->\n{{short description|Younger sister of North Korean leader Kim Jong-un}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2018}}\n{{Korean name|Kim}}\n{{Infobox officeholder \n| name        = Kim Yo-jong\n| image       = Moon Jae-in meeting with North Korean delegates at Blue House (cropped).jpg\n| image_size   = 220px \n|office = First Deputy Director of the [[Propaganda and Agitation Department]]\n|term_start = November 2014\n|2blankname = Director\n|2namedata = [[Kim Ki-nam]]<br>[[Pak Kwang-ho]]<br>[[Ri Il-hwan]]\n|predecessor = ''Office established''\n| 1blankname = {{nowrap|[[Supreme Leader of North Korea|Supreme Leader]]}}\n| 1namedata = [[Kim Jong-un]]\n| alt         = \n| caption     = Kim Yo-jong in February 2018\n| birth_name  = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1988|9|26|}}\n| birth_place = [[Pyongyang]], [[North Korea]]\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = [[North Korea]]n\n| other_names = \n| occupation  = \n| known_for   = \n| alma_mater  = [[Kim Il-sung Military University]]\n| parents     = [[Kim Jong-il]]<br />[[Ko Yong-hui]]\n| signature   = Signature of Kim Yo-jong.svg\n| signature_alt   = Signature of Kim Yo-jong\n| module      = {{Infobox Korean name|child=yes\n| hangul  = \uae40\uc5ec\uc815\n| hanja   = {{linktext|lang=ko-Hant|\u91d1|\u8207|\u6b63}}\n| rr      = Gim Yeojeong\n| mr      = Kim Y\u014fj\u014fng\n| context = north}}\n}}\n\n'''Kim Yo-jong''' ({{lang-ko|\uae40\uc5ec\uc815}}, born 26 September 1988)<ref>{{cite news |script-title=ko:\ud1b5\uc77c\ubd80, \uae40\uc5ec\uc815 '1988\ub144\uc0dd' \uacf5\uc2dd \ud310\ub2e8\u2026\uc791\ub144\uc5d4 '\uc5f0\ub3c4\ubbf8\uc0c1' \ud45c\uae30 |url=http://news.mk.co.kr/newsRead.php?year=2018&no=806316 |accessdate=4 January 2019 |work=MK News |date=27 December 2018 |language=Korean}}</ref><ref name=leaderwatch>{{cite news|url=http://nkleadershipwatch.wordpress.com/kim-family/kim-yo-jong/|title=Kim Yo Jong|publisher=North Korea Leadership Watch|date=6 May 2016|access-date=18 December 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190213133651/https://nkleadershipwatch.wordpress.com/kim-family/kim-yo-jong/|archive-date=13 February 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref> is a North Korean politician. She is the youngest daughter of former supreme leader [[Kim Jong-il]]. Her brother is [[Kim Jong-un]], the current supreme leader. She is an alternate member of the [[Politburo of the Workers' Party of Korea|Politburo]] (Political Bureau) and vice director of the [[Propaganda and Agitation Department]] of the [[Workers' Party of Korea]] (WPK).\n\n==Early life==\nKim Yo-jong was born to [[Kim Jong-il]] and his wife [[Ko Yong-hui]] on 26 September 1988.<ref name=leaderwatch/> She and her brother, Kim Jong-un, are said to have a close relationship,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dw.com/en/kim-yo-jong-who-is-the-north-korean-leaders-mysterious-sister/a-40862677|title=Kim Yo Jong: Who is the North Korean leader's mysterious sister? {{!}} News {{!}} DW {{!}} 8 October 2017|last=(www.dw.com)|first=Deutsche Welle|website=DW.COM|language=en|access-date=9 October 2017}}</ref> due to shared isolated years while studying together in [[Switzerland]] from 1996 to 2000, and in North Korea, \"where social and emotional isolation appears to have been a defining force in their early lives\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.38north.org/2015/08/mmadden081415/|title=North Korea\u2019s New Propagandist?|date=14 August 2015|work=38 North|access-date=9 October 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> possibly because their father Kim Jong-Il wanted to bring them up away from the influence of his father [[Kim Il-sung]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.newsweek.com/who-kim-yo-jong-kim-jong-un-sister-becoming-north-korea-most-powerful-woman-802439|title=Who is Kim Jong Un\u2019s sister? Kim Jo Yong is becoming North Korea\u2019s most powerful woman|last=O'Connor|first=Tom|date=9 February 2018|work=Newsweek|access-date=10 February 2018|language=en}}</ref> She may have studied at the [[Kim Il-sung Military University]] after her return.<ref name=leaderwatch/> She also studied computer science at [[Kim Il-sung University]] where she is said to have studied with [[Kim Eun-gyong]], the daughter of [[North Korean abductions of Japanese citizens|Japanese abductee]] [[Megumi Yokota]].<ref name=\"kore_Abdu\">{{Cite web | title = Abductee\u2019s daughter is favorite of Kim\u2019s sister | author = Kim Hee-Jin | work = [[Korea JoongAng Daily]] | date = 19 March 2014 | accessdate = 30 April 2015 | url = http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=2986592 }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nKim's first public appearance was at a photo session for participants at the {{ill|3rd Conference of the Workers' Party of Korea|ko|\uc870\uc120\ub85c\ub3d9\ub2f9 \uc81c3\ucc28 \ub300\ud45c\uc790\ud68c|lt=3rd Conference of the WPK}} in September 2010, when she stood next to her father's personal secretary and alleged mistress [[Kim Ok]].<ref name=\"kji-youngest\">{{cite news|location=South Korea|url=http://nkleadershipwatch.wordpress.com/2013/07/22/kji-youngest-daughter-working-as-events-manager-for-kju/|title=KJI Youngest Daughter Working as Events Manager for KJU?|work=North Korea Leadership Watch|date=22 July 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131222045126/http://nkleadershipwatch.wordpress.com/2013/07/22/kji-youngest-daughter-working-as-events-manager-for-kju/|archivedate=22 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nKim Yo-jong was given much publicity during the funeral service for Kim Jong-il in December 2011, when she appeared several times alongside her brother Kim Jong-un or leading funeral processions of central officials, despite not even being a funeral committee member, and she was never named. She was then reportedly given a position under the [[National Defence Commission]] at the beginning of 2012 as tour manager for Kim Jong-un,<ref>{{cite news |location=South Korea |url=http://www.hani.co.kr/arti/english_edition/e_northkorea/596633.html/ |title=Kim Yo-jung is believed to have studied abroad and to share her older brother\u2019s ambition |publisher=Hankyoreh|date=22 July 2013}}</ref> but has not appeared in news reports except for November 2012, when the [[Korean Central Television]] showed her accompanying Kim Jong-un at a military riding ground.<ref>{{cite news |location=South Korea |url= http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/search1/2603000000.html?cid=AEN20121121007000325 |title=North Korea Newsletter No. 237 |publisher=Yonhap News Agency |date=22 November 2013}}</ref> She was officially mentioned for the first time on 9 March 2014, as she accompanied her brother in voting for the [[Supreme People's Assembly]]. Kim Yo-jong was identified as a \"senior official\" of the [[Central Committee of the Workers' Party of Korea|WPK Central Committee]].<ref>{{cite news|location=North Korea (site in Japan) |url=http://www.kcna.co.jp/item/2014/201403/news09/20140309-19ee.html |title=Kim Jong Un Visits Kim Il Sung University of Politics and Takes Part in Election of Deputy to SPA |publisher=Korean Central News Agency |date=9 March 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140310111435/http://www.kcna.co.jp/item/2014/201403/news09/20140309-19ee.html |archivedate=10 March 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn October 2014, she was reported to have possibly taken over state duties for her ailing brother while he underwent medical treatment.<ref>{{Cite web |url= http://www.ibtimes.com/has-kim-yo-jong-taken-over-kim-jong-un-sister-assumes-north-korea-state-duties-while-1698550 |title=Has Kim Yo-Jong Taken Over For Kim Jong Un? Sister Assumes North Korea State Duties While Brother Undergoes Medical Treatment |date=2 October 2014|accessdate=3 October 2014|work=International Business Times|last=Silva |first=Cristina}}</ref>\n\n[[File:President Moon in PyeongChang 2018 opening ceremony-02.jpg|thumb|Kim Yo-jong, [[President of South Korea|South Korean President]] [[Moon Jae-in]] and [[Vice President of the United States|U.S. Vice President]] [[Mike Pence]] at the [[2018 Winter Olympics opening ceremony]]]]\nIn November 2014, she was reported to be Vice Director of the Workers Party's [[Propaganda and Agitation Department]] (PAD).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/11/28/us-northkorea-politics-kim-idUSKCN0JC04A20141128|title=North Korea's 'princess' moves closer to center of power|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151126100412/http://www.reuters.com/article/2014/11/30/us-northkorea-politics-kim-idUSKCN0JC04A20141130|archive-date=26 November 2015|date=29 November 2014|last1=Pearson|first1=James|author2=Ju-min Park|agency=Reuters}}</ref> In July 2015, reports saw her as playing the role of ''de facto'' leader of the department, with nominal director [[Kim Ki-nam]] in a supporting role.<ref>{{cite news |location=UK |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/jul/24/kim-jong-un-sister-promoted-north-korea |title=Kim Jong-un's sister promoted to run 'idolisation projects' in North Korea |work=The Guardian |date=24 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | title = Kim Yo Jong in de facto power of PAD | author = Lee Sang Yong | work = Daily NK | date = 20 July 2015 | accessdate = 28 May 2018 | url = http://english.dailynk.com/english/read.php?num=13352&cataId=nk01500 }}</ref> She also holds a vice-ministerial post, but her portfolio is not known.<ref name=\"engl_TheC\"/> She regularly accompanies Kim Jong-un on his \"field guidance\" trips.<ref name=afp>{{cite web |url=https://news.yahoo.com/n-koreas-kim-jong-un-executed-15-top-090014485.html |title=N. Korea's Kim Jong-un executed 15 top officials: S. Korea spy agency |work=Yahoo! News|agency=AFP |date=29 April 2015|accessdate=29 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[File:2018 inter-Korean summit 02.jpg|thumb|Talks inside the [[Peace House]] in April 2018]]\nShe has been said to be the driving force behind the development of her brother's [[North Korean cult of personality|cult of personality]], modelled after that of their grandfather, [[Kim Il-sung]].<ref name=\":0\" /> This would help explain changes in the way state policies are depicted in the media, as well as differences in reporting.<ref name=\":0\" /> [[Thae Yong-ho]], a North Korean defector and former diplomat, said in 2017 that Kim Yo-jong organised all major public events in North Korea. Kim Yo-jong was said to have encouraged her brother to present an image of a \"man of the people\" with, for example, rides on fairground attractions and his friendship with the basketball star [[Dennis Rodman]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/sister-helps-kim-strut-his-stuff-as-key-missile-test-looms-jjf8gdvzk|title=Sister helps Kim strut his stuff as key missile test looms|last=Sherwell|first=Phillip|date=8 January 2017|newspaper=The Times|access-date=15 February 2017|work=|language=en|url-access=registration |via=}}</ref><ref name=\"Justin\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/oct/09/kim-yo-jong-sister-brains-behind-kim-jong-uns-image|title=Meet Kim Yo-jong, the sister who is the brains behind Kim Jong-un's image|last=McCurry|first=Justin|date=9 October 2017|work=The Guardian|access-date=8 January 2018|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2017, she was placed on the [[United States Department of the Treasury|US Treasury]]'s [[Specially Designated Nationals List]] in response to human rights abuses in North Korea.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-northkorea-sanctions/u-s-slaps-sanctions-on-seven-north-koreans-two-dprk-entities-idUSKBN14V2HS|title=U.S. blacklists North Korean officials over rights abuses|date= 11 January 2017|work=Reuters|access-date=9 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Kim Yo-jong was made an alternate member of the [[Politburo of the Workers' Party of Korea|politburo]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-northkorea-missiles-kim/kim-jong-un-praises-nuclear-program-promotes-sister-to-center-of-power-idUSKBN1CD03V|title=Kim Jong Un praises nuclear program, promotes sister to center of power|publisher=Reuters|date=8 October 2017}}</ref> only the second woman to be appointed to this decision-making body.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/kims-sister-act-the-rapid-ascent-of-north-koreas-new-top-aide-1518181299|title=Behind the Rapid Rise of Kim Jong Un\u2019s Younger Sister|last=Gale|first=Alastair|date=9 February 2018|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=10 February 2018|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> As it was previously speculated,<ref>{{cite news |location=United Kingdom |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/northkorea/10499642/Kim-Jong-un-preparing-to-purge-aunt.html |title=Kim Jong-un 'preparing to purge aunt' |work=The Telegraph |date=6 December 2013}}</ref> her ascension to the country's supreme governing body may indicate that she is Kim Jong-un\u2019s replacement for his aunt, [[Kim Kyong-hui]] (with whom Kim Yo-jong is said to have a good relationship),<ref name=kji-youngest/> who has not played an active role in his regime.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/oct/09/kim-yo-jong-sister-brains-behind-kim-jong-uns-image|title=Meet Kim Yo-jong, the sister who is the brains behind Kim Jong-un's image|last=McCurry|first=Justin|date=9 October 2017|work=The Guardian|access-date=9 October 2017|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> It has also been hinted that her newly assigned position would also put her in charge of the [[State Security Department]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2018/01/25/2018012501295.html#top|title=Kim Jong-un 'Puts Sister in Charge of State Security'|access-date=30 January 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 February 2018, Yo-jong attended the [[2018 Winter Olympics opening ceremony]] in [[Pyeongchang]], South Korea. This was the first time that a member of the ruling [[Kim dynasty (North Korea)|Kim dynasty]] had visited South Korea since the [[Korean War]].<ref name=\"theg_USvi\">{{Cite web | title = US vice-president skips Olympics dinner in snub to North Korea officials | last = Haas | first = Benjamin | work = the Guardian | date = 9 February 2018 | access-date = 9 February 2018 | url = https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/feb/09/kim-jong-uns-sister-arrives-in-south-korea-for-winter-olympics}}</ref> She attended the meeting with [[President of South Korea|South Korean President]] [[Moon Jae-in]] on 10 February, and revealed she was dispatched as a special envoy of Kim Jong-un and delivered a personally written letter from Kim to Moon.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/nation/2018/02/103_243936.html|title=South Korean president invited to North Korea|date=10 February 2018|work=koreatimes|access-date=11 February 2018|language=en}}</ref> Kim was later part of her brother's team during the [[2018 North Korea\u2013United States Singapore Summit]]<ref>https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/kim-jong-un-meets-pm-lee-ahead-of-trump-kim-summit-10414948</ref> and the [[2019 North Korea\u2013United States Hanoi Summit]]. Her involvement in diplomatic affairs continued as she issued an official statement in March 2020 from her capacity as first deputy department director of the party.<ref name=\"statement\">{{Cite web | title = Kim Jong Un sister's first official remarks hint at higher status |\n work = Al Jazeera | date = 3 March 2020 | accessdate = 13 April 2020 | url = https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/kim-jong-sister-official-remarks-hint-higher-status-200304024330626.html }}</ref>\n\nAccording to Kim Yong-hyun, a professor of North Korean studies at Dongguk University in Seoul, and others, the promotion of  Kim Yo-jong and others is a sign that \"the Kim Jong-un regime has ended its co-existence with the remnants of the previous Kim Jong-il regime by carrying out a generational replacement in the party\u2019s key elite posts\".<ref name=\"Justin\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-5205399/Kim-Jong-uns-sister-sits-yards-promotion.html|title=Kim Jong-un's sister sits just yards from the tyrant after promotion|work=Mail Online|access-date=8 January 2018}}</ref> ''Newsweek''{{'}}s Tom O'Connor echoed this opinion, writing that Kim Yo-jong's rise to power was part of Kim Jong-un's overall plan to appoint younger people in place of his father's older elites who may have harboured doubts about the younger Kim Jong-un's ability to lead North Korea.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nKim was elected to the [[Supreme People's Assembly]] during the [[2019 North Korean parliamentary election]],<ref name=NorthKoreaElection>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/amp/world-asia-47535658|title=North Korea election: Surprise as leader Kim Jong-un 'not on ballot|work=BBC News|access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> representing [[Killimgil]].<ref>{{Cite web |script-title=ko:\ubd81 \uae40\uc815\uc740, \ucd5c\uace0\uc778\ubbfc\ud68c\uc758 \ub300\uc758\uc6d0 \ucc98\uc74c \ube60\uc838: (\ucd94\uac00) \ubd81 \uc5b8\ub860, 687\uba85 \ub300\uc758\uc6d0 \uba85\ub2e8 \ubc1c\ud45c...\ub2f9 \ubd80\uc704\uc6d0\uc7a5\ub4e4 \ud3ec\ud568 (\uba85\ub2e8) |author=Jo Jung-hoon |work=Tongil News |date=12 March 2019 |access-date=18 March 2019 |url= http://www.tongilnews.com/news/articleView.html?idxno=128110 |language=ko  }}</ref> In April of the same year, she was briefly removed from the party politburo, before being reinstated in April 2020.<ref name=KYJreinstated>{{Cite news|url=https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20200412000553325|title=(3rd LD) N.K. leader holds politburo meeting to discuss anti-virus measures\n|work=Yonhap|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref> On April 21, 2020, rumors of Kim Jong-un's death has pushed Kim Yo-Jong into focus as the possible successor of the government's leadership in North Korea.<ref name=KYJleader>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newsweek.com/who-kim-jong-uns-sister-north-korea-leaders-reported-health-problems-push-kim-yo-jong-focus-1499135|title=WHO IS KIM JONG UN'S SISTER? NORTH KOREA LEADER'S REPORTED HEALTH PROBLEMS PUSH KIM YO JONG INTO FOCUS|work=DAVID BRENNAN |access-date=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn January 2015, she reportedly married Choe Song,<ref>(2 January 2015) [https://blogs.wsj.com/korearealtime/2015/01/02/kim-jong-uns-little-sister-married-son-of-top-regime-official-report-says/ Kim Jong Un\u2019s Little Sister Married Son of Top Regime Official, Report Says] Wall Street Journal, Asia, Retrieved 16 January 2015</ref> the second son of government official [[Choe Ryong-hae]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/northkorea/2015/01/02/97/0401000000AEN20150102006900315F.html|title=NK leader's sister weds son of Choe Ryong-hae: sources|publisher=Yonhap News Agency}}</ref> However, South Korean government sources have disputed the accuracy of these reports.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}} Kim Yo-jong was expecting a child in May 2015. The father, not identified, is thought to be a fellow alumnus of Kim Il-sung university and either an official at [[Room 39]] of the [[Workers' Party of Korea]] (WPK) or working at a military unit responsible for guarding the country's leader.<ref name=\"engl_TheC\">{{Cite web | title = The Chosun Ilbo (English Edition): Daily News from Korea \u2013 Kim Jong-un's Sister to Have Baby in May | work = [[Chosun Ilbo]] | date = 30 April 2014 | accessdate = 30 April 2014 | url = http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2015/04/30/2015043001119.html }}</ref>\n{{Kim Jong-il family}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|North Korea|Biography|Politics}}\n*[[Kim Kyong-hui]]\n*[[Kim Song-hye]]\n*[[Kim Sol-song]]\n*[[Politics of North Korea]]\n*[[Ro Song-sil]]\n*[[Women in North Korea]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Commons category-inline}}\n\n{{Family of Kim Jong-il}}\n{{Women in North Korean politics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kim, Yo-jong}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Kim dynasty (North Korea)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Supreme People's Assembly]]\n[[Category:North Korean women in politics]]\n[[Category:Workers' Party of Korea politicians]]\n[[Category:Kim Il-sung University alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Pyongyang]]\n[[Category:North Korean people of Japanese descent]]\n[[Category:North Korean politicians of Japanese descent]]\n", "name_user": "Sealle", "label": "safe", "comment": "(GR)File renamed:File:Moon Jae-in meeting with North Korean delegates at Blue House (cropped).jpg\u2192File:Kim Yo-jong at Blue House (cropped).jpgunsuitable name for a crop", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kim_Yo-jong"}
{"title_page": "Dino (The Flintstones)", "text_new": "{{DISPLAYTITLE:Dino (''The Flintstones'')}}\n{{More citations needed|date=January 2011}}\n{{Infobox character\n| color              = purple\n| name               = Dino\n| series             = [[The Flintstones]]\n| image              = Dino_from_\"The_Flintstones\".gif\n| image_size         = 150px\n| first              = The Flintstones (1960)\n| creator            = [[Hanna-Barbera]]\n| voice              = [[Mel Blanc]] (1960\u20131987, 1994, 2000)<br>Jerry Mann (1961)<br>[[Frank Welker]] (1981\u20132001)<br>[[Bill Farmer]] (2000)<br>[[Mark Mangini]] (2001)<br>[[Eric Bauza]] (2015\u2013present)\n| species            = ''Snorkasaurus''\n| spouse             = Juliet\n| gender             = Male\n| children           = 15\n}}\n'''Dino''' ({{IPAc-en|pron|\u02c8|d|i\u02d0|n|o\u028a}}) is a [[character (arts)|fictional character]] featured in the [[Hanna-Barbera]] animated [[television series]] ''[[The Flintstones]]'', and its [[spin-off (media)|spin-off]]s and [[feature film]]s. He is a pet dinosaur of the series' main characters, [[Fred Flintstone|Fred]] and [[Wilma Flintstone]].<ref>{{cite news|title= The Flintstones' 50th anniversary: 15 things you don't know|work= Daily Telegraph |date=2010-09-30|url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/8034627/The-Flintstones-50th-anniversary-15-things-you-dont-know.html|accessdate=2010-10-01|location=London|first=Heidi|last=Blake}}</ref> Dino debuted in the opening credits of the pilot episode of ''The Flintstones'', but is not mentioned by name until the first season's fourth episode, \"No Help Wanted.\"\n\n==Background==\nIn the series, Dino serves the role of a pet dog, and exhibits the characteristics of a typical domesticated canine.\n\nDino is a [[prosauropod]]-like [[dinosaur]], a Snorkasaurus. Dino is a relatively small dinosaur, only slightly larger than the humans of his time, smaller than [[mammoth]]s that appear in the series, and much smaller than the numerous sauropods that appear as work animals in the series (a full-sized sauropod appears as a crane in the opening sequence, and oversized \"[[Brontosaurus|bronto]] ribs\" the size of an automobile are seen in the closing credits).\n\nA recurring gag in the series is Fred coming home from work, and Dino gets excited and knocks him down and licks his face. But no matter how hard he tries to the contrary, Fred usually gives in to Dino's ticklish and wet doglike kisses. Dino frequently exhibits human emotions, nearly \"talking,\" and can also be moved to anger, at which point he snarls and snaps, especially when Fred tries to lie either to or in front of him, which he can always tell. He also loves to play with [[Pebbles Flintstone|Pebbles]] and [[Bamm-Bamm Rubble|Bamm-Bamm]], the Flintstones' and Rubbles' respective offspring; these characters are introduced in the middle part of the series. In the episode \"Hop Happy\" Dino meets Hoppy, the Rubbles' new pet hopperoo. At first, Dino and Fred get scared, thinking he's a giant mouse, but they eventually become best friends after Hoppy helps Dino rescue their owners in an accident.\n\nAlthough he is usually immune, Dino does take a couple of brief stabs at romance.  The first comes in the episode, \"Dino Goes Hollyrock\", which originally aired on September 14, 1962.  In it, Dino falls in love with female TV star sauropod \"Sassie\" (an obvious takeoff on \"[[Lassie (1954 TV series)|Lassie]]\") and then becomes her co-star on her TV show.  However, after she removes her false eyelashes and wig, he is shocked that she turned out to be an ugly, talented sauropod that could be beautified.  The second comes in the episode, \"Dino and Juliet\", which originally aired on November 26, 1964.  In it, Dino falls in love with the new neighbor's female sauropod (Juliet).  Their romance, which results in the birth of 15 puppies, helps end the feud between Fred and the new neighbor, Mr. Loudrock.\n\nAlthough Dino had already appeared earlier in the series' first season (such as the episode \"No Help Wanted\" and \"Arthur Quarry's Dance Class\" - these episodes were made after the \"Snorkasaurus Hunter\" but aired before), Dino is portrayed quite differently in the first season's 18th episode \"The Snorkasaurus Hunter.\" In this episode, Fred and his friend [[Barney Rubble]] are on a camping trip, trying to hunt a snorkasaurus. Unlike Dino's other appearances, the snorkasaurus in this episode speaks and behaves toward Fred and Barney in a manner similar to comedian [[Phil Silvers]]. At the end of the episode, the Flintstones take in the dinosaur; the snorkasaurus (called \"Dino\" at one point by Wilma) is seen acting like a butler for the Flintstones: answering the telephone, dusting, and ironing. Dino in this episode also has purple skin instead of his varying pink-to-red color, which seems to vary from episode-to-episode during this early period, but is permanently purple after this episode. After this episode, Dino is permanently portrayed as behaving in a doglike fashion.<ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0580278/</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.topthat.net/webrock/faq/faq10.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-01-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120513034318/http://www.topthat.net/webrock/faq/faq10.htm |archivedate=2012-05-13 }}</ref>\n\nDino's origins are explained in the episode \"Dino Disappears\", which originally aired on October 10, 1963.  In it, Wilma states that Dino followed Fred home because Fred was playing with him.  Fred counters by saying he was merely trying to chase him away. This seems to refer to the episode \"Snorkasaurus Hunter\" where Fred and Barney's playing was actually hunting him down and Dino's following him was actually Dino sneaking onto the car.\n\nPost-original series, Dino appears in most of the series' spin-offs, except during the first season of ''[[The Pebbles and Bamm-Bamm Show]]''. There, Dino is replaced by Wooly, a dwarf mammoth, as the Flintstone family's pet. However, starting with the following series ''[[The Flintstone Comedy Hour]]'', Dino once again becomes a regular character.\n\nIn the 1980-1982 series ''[[The Flintstone Comedy Show]]'', Dino is featured in his own segment, \"[[The Flintstone Comedy Show (1980 TV series)#Dino and Cavemouse|Dino and Cavemouse]],\" where Dino tries futilely to capture a pesky [[mouse]] in the Flintstone household. The segments bear some similarities to classic cat-and-mouse cartoons such as ''[[Tom and Jerry]]''.\n\nDino later appears as a puppy in 1986-1988 series ''[[The Flintstone Kids]]'' (including his own segment, \"Dino's Dilemmas\"), as Pebbles and Bamm-Bamm's babysitter in the short-lived 1996 series ''[[Cave Kids]]'', and also starred in his own two 7-minute short cartoons, ''[[Dino: Stay Out!]]'' (1995) and ''[[Dino: The Great Egg-Scape]]'' (1997).\n\nIn 2020, Dino is featured in the new series ''[[Yabba-Dabba Dinosaurs]]''. Similar to ''[[Cave Kids]]'', the show focuses on the lives of Pebbles and Bamm-Bamm, who are joined by Dino for many adventures in the Stone Age.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Amidi |first1=Amid |title=Boomerang Announces 2 New Streaming Series: \u2018Yabba-Dabba Dinosaurs!\u2019 and \u2018Scooby-Doo And Guess Who?\u2019 |url=https://www.cartoonbrew.com/internet-television/boomerang-announces-2-new-streaming-series-yabba-dabba-dinosaurs-and-scooby-doo-and-guess-who-158604.html |accessdate=16 March 2020 |work=Cartoon Brew |date=May 24, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Other media==\n[[File:Dino Harikalar Diyari Flintstones 06029 nevit.jpg|thumbnail|right|Dino statue (right), along with [[Fred Flintstone]] (left).]]\nDino appears in both live-action movies. He isn't seen very often in the first film, ''[[The Flintstones (film)|The Flintstones]]'' (1994). Dino was created with both computer-generated imagery and as a puppet from [[Jim Henson's Creature Shop]], while archival audio from the original series was used to serve as Dino's voice.{{citation needed|date=April 2013}}\n\nHowever, in the second film, ''[[The Flintstones in Viva Rock Vegas]]'' (2000), Dino has more screen time; he appears here as a puppy. Fred won Dino's egg as a prize after winning a carnival game. Initially, Fred didn't think much of the egg as he felt that the creatures inside never live long. On a [[Ferris wheel]], just as Fred and Wilma are about to kiss, Dino's egg hatches and he takes an immediate attachment to Fred, believing him to be his mother. (This, of course, contradicts Dino's origin in the original series.)\n\n==Filmography==\n===Television shows===\n* ''[[The Flintstones]]'' (1960\u20131966)\n* ''[[The Flintstone Comedy Hour]]'' (1972\u20131974)\n* ''[[Fred Flintstone and Friends]]'' (1977\u20131978)\n* ''[[The New Fred and Barney Show]]'' (1979)\n* ''[[Fred and Barney Meet the Thing]]'' (1979)\n* ''[[Fred and Barney Meet the Shmoo]]'' (1979\u20131980)\n* ''[[The Flintstone Comedy Show]]'' (1980\u20131982)\n* ''[[The Flintstone Funnies]]'' (1982\u20131984)\n* ''[[The Flintstone Kids]]'' (1986\u20131988)\n* ''[[What a Cartoon!]]'' \u2013 featuring ''[[Dino: Stay Out!]]'' (1995) and ''[[Dino: The Great Egg-Scape]]'' (1997)\n* ''[[Cave Kids]]'' (1996)\n* ''[[Yabba-Dabba Dinosaurs]]'' (2020)\n\n===Films and Specials===\n* ''[[The Man Called Flintstone]]'' (1966)\n* ''[[Energy: A National Issue]]'' (1977)\n* ''[[A Flintstone Christmas]]'' (1977)\n* ''[[The Flintstones: Little Big League]]'' (1978)\n* ''[[The Flintstones: Fred's Final Fling]]'' (1980)\n* ''[[The Flintstones: Wind-Up Wilma]]'' (1981)\n* ''[[The Flintstones: Jogging Fever]]'' (1981)\n* ''[[The Jetsons Meet the Flintstones]]'' (1987)\n* ''[[The Flintstone Kids' \"Just Say No\" Special]]'' (1988)\n* ''[[Hanna-Barbera's 50th: A Yabba Dabba Doo Celebration|A Yabba Dabba Doo Celebration: 50 Years of Hanna-Barbera]]'' (1989)\n* ''[[I Yabba-Dabba Do!]]'' (1993)\n* ''[[Hollyrock-a-Bye Baby]]'' (1993)\n* ''[[A Flintstone Family Christmas]]'' (1993)\n* ''[[The Flintstones (film)|The Flintstones]]'' (1994)\n* ''[[A Flintstones Christmas Carol]]'' (1994)\n* ''[[The Flintstones in Viva Rock Vegas]]'' (2000)\n* ''[[The Flintstones: On the Rocks]]'' (2001)\n* ''[[The Flintstones & WWE: Stone Age SmackDown!]]'' (2015)\n\n==Portrayal==\nDino's barks and sound effects were provided by [[Mel Blanc]] for 27 years, from 1960\u20131987; archive audio of Blanc was used for Dino in the [[The Flintstones (film)|1994 live-action film]] and [[The Flintstones in Viva Rock Vegas|its prequel in 2000]]. Jerry Mann provided the speaking voice of Dino in the 1961 episode \"The Snorkasaurus Hunter\". [[Frank Welker]] provided Dino's vocal effects for 20 years, from ''[[The Flintstones: Jogging Fever]]'' in 1981, until ''[[The Flintstones: On the Rocks]]'' in 2001 (a role he shared with [[Mark Mangini]]). [[Bill Farmer]] provided the vocal effects in the 2000 video game ''[[The Flintstones: Bedrock Bowling]]''. [[Mark Mangini]] shared vocal duties with Frank Welker for ''The Flintstones: On the Rocks''. In 2015, [[Eric Bauza]] provided the vocal effects for the direct-to-video ''[[The Flintstones & WWE: Stone Age SmackDown!]]''.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{The Flintstones}}\n{{Hanna-Barbera}}\n\n[[Category:Television characters introduced in 1960]]\n[[Category:Fictional dinosaurs]]\n[[Category:The Flintstones characters]]\n[[Category:Post Foods characters]]\n[[Category:Male characters in animation]]\n", "text_old": "{{DISPLAYTITLE:Dino (''The Flintstones'')}}\n{{More citations needed|date=January 2011}}\n{{Infobox character\n| color              = purple\n| name               = Dino\n| series             = [[The Flintstones]]\n| image              = Dino_from_\"The_Flintstones\".gif\n| image_size         = 150px\n| first              = The Flintstones (1960)\n| creator            = [[Hanna-Barbera]]\n| voice              = [[Mel Blanc]] (1960\u20131987, 1994, 2000)<br>Jerry Mann (1961)<br>[[Frank Welker]] (1981\u20132001)<br>[[Bill Farmer]] (2000)<br>[[Mark Mangini]] (2001)<br>[[Eric Bauza]] (2015\u2013present)\n| species            = ''Snorkasaurus''\n| spouse             = Juliet\n| gender             = Male\n| children           = 15\n}}\n'''Dino''' ({{IPAc-en|pron|\u02c8|d|i\u02d0|n|o\u028a}}) is a [[character (arts)|fictional character]] featured in the [[Hanna-Barbera]] animated [[television series]] ''[[The Flintstones]]'', and its [[spin-off (media)|spin-off]]s and [[feature film]]s. He is a pet dinosaur of the series' main characters, [[Fred Flintstone|Fred]] and [[Wilma Flintstone]].<ref>{{cite news|title= The Flintstones' 50th anniversary: 15 things you don't know|work= Daily Telegraph |date=2010-09-30|url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/8034627/The-Flintstones-50th-anniversary-15-things-you-dont-know.html|accessdate=2010-10-01|location=London|first=Heidi|last=Blake}}</ref> Dino debuted in the opening credits of the pilot episode of ''The Flintstones'', but is not mentioned by name until the first season's fourth episode, \"No Help Wanted.\"\n\n==Background==\nIn the series, Dino serves the role of a pet dog, and exhibits the characteristics of a typical domesticated canine.\n\nDino is a [[prosauropod]]-like [[dinosaur]], a Snorkasaurus. Dino is a relatively small dinosaur, only slightly larger than the humans of his time, smaller than [[mammoth]]s that appear in the series, and much smaller than the numerous sauropods that appear as work animals in the series (a full-sized sauropod appears as a crane in the opening sequence, and oversized \"[[Brontosaurus|bronto]] ribs\" the size of an automobile are seen in the closing credits).\n\nA recurring gag in the series is Fred coming home from work, and Dino gets excited and knocks him down and licks his face. But no matter how hard he tries to the contrary, Fred usually gives in to Dino's ticklish and wet doglike kisses. Dino frequently exhibits human emotions, nearly \"talking,\" and can also be moved to anger, at which point he snarls and snaps, especially when Fred tries to lie either to or in front of him, which he can always tell. He also loves to play with [[Pebbles Flintstone|Pebbles]] and [[Bamm-Bamm Rubble|Bamm-Bamm]], the Flintstones' and Rubbles' respective offspring; these characters are introduced in the middle part of the series. In the episode \"Hop Happy\" Dino meets Hoppy, the Rubbles' new pet hopperoo. At first, Dino and Fred get scared, thinking he's a giant mouse, but they eventually become best friends after Hoppy helps Dino rescue their owners in an accident.\n\nAlthough he is usually immune, Dino does take a couple of brief stabs at romance.  The first comes in the episode, \"Dino Goes Hollyrock\", which originally aired on September 14, 1962.  In it, Dino falls in love with female TV star sauropod \"Sassie\" (an obvious takeoff on \"[[Lassie (1954 TV series)|Lassie]]\") and then becomes her co-star on her TV show.  However, after she removes her false eyelashes and wig, he is shocked that she turned out to be an ugly, talented sauropod that could be beautified.  The second comes in the episode, \"Dino and Juliet\", which originally aired on November 26, 1964.  In it, Dino falls in love with the new neighbor's female sauropod (Juliet).  Their romance, which results in the birth of 15 puppies, helps end the feud between Fred and the new neighbor, Mr. Loudrock.\n\nAlthough Dino had already appeared earlier in the series' first season (such as the episode \"No Help Wanted\" and \"Arthur Quarry's Dance Class\" - these episodes were made after the \"Snorkasaurus Hunter\" but aired before), Dino is portrayed quite differently in the first season's 18th episode \"The Snorkasaurus Hunter.\" In this episode, Fred and his friend [[Barney Rubble]] are on a camping trip, trying to hunt a snorkasaurus. Unlike Dino's other appearances, the snorkasaurus in this episode speaks and behaves toward Fred and Barney in a manner similar to comedian [[Phil Silvers]]. At the end of the episode, the Flintstones take in the dinosaur; the snorkasaurus (called \"Dino\" at one point by Wilma) is seen acting like a butler for the Flintstones: answering the telephone, dusting, and ironing. Dino in this episode also has purple skin instead of his varying pink-to-red color, which seems to vary from episode-to-episode during this early period, but is permanently purple after this episode. After this episode, Dino is permanently portrayed as behaving in a doglike fashion.<ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0580278/</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.topthat.net/webrock/faq/faq10.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-01-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120513034318/http://www.topthat.net/webrock/faq/faq10.htm |archivedate=2012-05-13 }}</ref>\n\nDino's origins are explained in the episode \"Dino Disappears\", which originally aired on October 10, 1963.  In it, Wilma states that Dino followed Fred home because Fred was playing with him.  Fred counters by saying he was merely trying to chase him away. This seems to refer to the episode \"Snorkasaurus Hunter\" where Fred and Barney's playing was actually hunting him down and Dino's following him was actually Dino sneaking onto the car.\n\nPost-original series, Dino appears in most of the series' spin-offs, except during the first season of ''[[The Pebbles and Bamm-Bamm Show]]''. There, Dino is replaced by Wooly, a dwarf mammoth, as the Flintstone family's pet. However, starting with the following series ''[[The Flintstone Comedy Hour]]'', Dino once again becomes a regular character.\n\nIn the 1980-1982 series ''[[The Flintstone Comedy Show]]'', Dino is featured in his own segment, \"[[The Flintstone Comedy Show (1980 TV series)#Dino and Cavemouse|Dino and Cavemouse]],\" where Dino tries futilely to capture a pesky [[mouse]] in the Flintstone household. The segments bear some similarities to classic cat-and-mouse cartoons such as ''[[Tom and Jerry]]''.\n\nDino later appears as a puppy in 1986-1988 series ''[[The Flintstone Kids]]'' (including his own segment, \"Dino's Dilemmas\"), as Pebbles and Bamm-Bamm's babysitter in the short-lived 1996 series ''[[Cave Kids]]'', and also starred in his own two 7-minute short cartoons, ''[[Dino: Stay Out!]]'' (1995) and ''[[Dino: The Great Egg-Scape]]'' (1997).\n\nDino is featured in the new 2020 series ''[[Yabba-Dabba Dinosaurs]]'' which, similar to ''[[Cave Kids]]'', focuses on the lives of Pebbles and Bamm-Bamm, who are joined by Dino for many adventures in the Stone Age.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Amidi |first1=Amid |title=Boomerang Announces 2 New Streaming Series: \u2018Yabba-Dabba Dinosaurs!\u2019 and \u2018Scooby-Doo And Guess Who?\u2019 |url=https://www.cartoonbrew.com/internet-television/boomerang-announces-2-new-streaming-series-yabba-dabba-dinosaurs-and-scooby-doo-and-guess-who-158604.html |accessdate=16 March 2020 |work=Cartoon Brew |date=May 24, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Other media==\n[[File:Dino Harikalar Diyari Flintstones 06029 nevit.jpg|thumbnail|right|Dino statue (right), along with [[Fred Flintstone]] (left).]]\nDino appears in both live-action movies. He isn't seen very often in the first film, ''[[The Flintstones (film)|The Flintstones]]'' (1994). Dino was created with both computer-generated imagery and as a puppet from [[Jim Henson's Creature Shop]], while archival audio from the original series was used to serve as Dino's voice.{{citation needed|date=April 2013}}\n\nHowever, in the second film, ''[[The Flintstones in Viva Rock Vegas]]'' (2000), Dino has more screen time; he appears here as a puppy. Fred won Dino's egg as a prize after winning a carnival game. Initially, Fred didn't think much of the egg as he felt that the creatures inside never live long. On a [[Ferris wheel]], just as Fred and Wilma are about to kiss, Dino's egg hatches and he takes an immediate attachment to Fred, believing him to be his mother. (This, of course, contradicts Dino's origin in the original series.)\n\n==Filmography==\n===Television shows===\n* ''[[The Flintstones]]'' (1960\u20131966)\n* ''[[The Flintstone Comedy Hour]]'' (1972\u20131974)\n* ''[[Fred Flintstone and Friends]]'' (1977\u20131978)\n* ''[[The New Fred and Barney Show]]'' (1979)\n* ''[[Fred and Barney Meet the Thing]]'' (1979)\n* ''[[Fred and Barney Meet the Shmoo]]'' (1979\u20131980)\n* ''[[The Flintstone Comedy Show]]'' (1980\u20131982)\n* ''[[The Flintstone Funnies]]'' (1982\u20131984)\n* ''[[The Flintstone Kids]]'' (1986\u20131988)\n* ''[[What a Cartoon!]]'' \u2013 featuring ''[[Dino: Stay Out!]]'' (1995) and ''[[Dino: The Great Egg-Scape]]'' (1997)\n* ''[[Cave Kids]]'' (1996)\n* ''[[Yabba-Dabba Dinosaurs]]'' (2020)\n\n===Films and Specials===\n* ''[[The Man Called Flintstone]]'' (1966)\n* ''[[Energy: A National Issue]]'' (1977)\n* ''[[A Flintstone Christmas]]'' (1977)\n* ''[[The Flintstones: Little Big League]]'' (1978)\n* ''[[The Flintstones: Fred's Final Fling]]'' (1980)\n* ''[[The Flintstones: Wind-Up Wilma]]'' (1981)\n* ''[[The Flintstones: Jogging Fever]]'' (1981)\n* ''[[The Jetsons Meet the Flintstones]]'' (1987)\n* ''[[The Flintstone Kids' \"Just Say No\" Special]]'' (1988)\n* ''[[Hanna-Barbera's 50th: A Yabba Dabba Doo Celebration|A Yabba Dabba Doo Celebration: 50 Years of Hanna-Barbera]]'' (1989)\n* ''[[I Yabba-Dabba Do!]]'' (1993)\n* ''[[Hollyrock-a-Bye Baby]]'' (1993)\n* ''[[A Flintstone Family Christmas]]'' (1993)\n* ''[[The Flintstones (film)|The Flintstones]]'' (1994)\n* ''[[A Flintstones Christmas Carol]]'' (1994)\n* ''[[The Flintstones in Viva Rock Vegas]]'' (2000)\n* ''[[The Flintstones: On the Rocks]]'' (2001)\n* ''[[The Flintstones & WWE: Stone Age SmackDown!]]'' (2015)\n\n==Portrayal==\nDino's barks and sound effects were provided by [[Mel Blanc]] for 27 years, from 1960\u20131987; archive audio of Blanc was used for Dino in the [[The Flintstones (film)|1994 live-action film]] and [[The Flintstones in Viva Rock Vegas|its prequel in 2000]]. Jerry Mann provided the speaking voice of Dino in the 1961 episode \"The Snorkasaurus Hunter\". [[Frank Welker]] provided Dino's vocal effects for 20 years, from ''[[The Flintstones: Jogging Fever]]'' in 1981, until ''[[The Flintstones: On the Rocks]]'' in 2001 (a role he shared with [[Mark Mangini]]). [[Bill Farmer]] provided the vocal effects in the 2000 video game ''[[The Flintstones: Bedrock Bowling]]''. [[Mark Mangini]] shared vocal duties with Frank Welker for ''The Flintstones: On the Rocks''. In 2015, [[Eric Bauza]] provided the vocal effects for the direct-to-video ''[[The Flintstones & WWE: Stone Age SmackDown!]]''.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{The Flintstones}}\n{{Hanna-Barbera}}\n\n[[Category:Television characters introduced in 1960]]\n[[Category:Fictional dinosaurs]]\n[[Category:The Flintstones characters]]\n[[Category:Post Foods characters]]\n[[Category:Male characters in animation]]\n", "name_user": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBackground", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dino_(The_Flintstones)"}
{"title_page": "Richard Huxford", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2012}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Richard Huxford\n| image          = Huxford and diallo at railhawks.jpg\n| image_size     = 200\n| caption        = Huxford (left) with [[Hamed Diallo]] during his days coaching at [[Carolina RailHawks]] in April 2009\n| fullname       = Richard John Huxford<ref name=\"Hugman\">{{Hugman|9808|accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref>\n| height         = {{height|ft=5|in=10}}<ref name=SB1/>\n| position       = [[Defender (association football)|Right back]]\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1969|7|25|df=y}}<ref name=\"Hugman\"/>\n| birth_place    = [[Scunthorpe]], England\n| death_date     = \n| youthyears1    = \u2013 \n| youthclubs1    = [[Scunthorpe United F.C.|Scunthorpe United]]\n| years1  = 1987\u20131989 | clubs1  = [[Matlock Town F.C.|Matlock Town]]                          | caps1  =    | goals1  =\n| years2  = 1989      | clubs2  = [[Burton Albion F.C.|Burton Albion]]                        | caps2  =    | goals2  = \n| years3  = 1989\u20131990 | clubs3  = [[Gainsborough Trinity F.C.|Gainsborough Trinity]]          | caps3  =    | goals3  =\n| years4  = 1990\u20131992 | clubs4  = [[Kettering Town F.C.|Kettering Town]]                      | caps4  =    | goals4  = \n| years5  = 1992\u20131993 | clubs5  = [[Barnet F.C.|Barnet]]                                      | caps5  = 33 | goals5  = 1\n| years6  = 1993\u20131995 | clubs6  = [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]]                                  | caps6  = 32 | goals6  = 0\n| years7  = 1994      | clubs7  = \u2192 [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] (loan)           | caps7  = 5  | goals7  = 0\n| years8  = 1994\u20131995 | clubs8  = \u2192 [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] (loan)             | caps8  = 14 | goals8  = 1\n| years9  = 1995\u20131997 | clubs9  = [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]]                      | caps9  = 47 | goals9  = 1\n| years10 = 1996      | clubs10 = \u2192 [[Peterborough United F.C.|Peterborough United]] (loan)   | caps10 = 7  | goals10 = 0\n| years11 = 1997\u20131998 | clubs11 = [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]]                                    | caps11 = 13 | goals11 = 0\n| years12 = 1998      | clubs12 = \u2192 [[Dunfermline Athletic F.C.|Dunfermline Athletic]] (loan) | caps12 = 10 | goals12 = 0\n| years13 = 1998\u20132000 | clubs13 = [[Dunfermline Athletic F.C.|Dunfermline Athletic]]          | caps13 = 27 | goals13 = 1\n| years14 = 2000\u20132001 | clubs14 = [[Alloa Athletic F.C.|Alloa Athletic]]                      | caps14 = 17 | goals14 = 0\n| years15 = 2001      | clubs15 = [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]]                    | caps15 = 6  | goals15 = 0\n| years16 = 2001\u20132002 | clubs16 = [[Berwick Rangers F.C.|Berwick Rangers]]                    | caps16 = 14 | goals16 = 0\n| years17 = 2003      | clubs17 = [[Ely City F.C.|Ely City]]                                  | caps17 = 5  | goals17 = 0\n| years18 = 2006\u20132007 | clubs18 = [[Elgin City F.C.|Elgin City]]                              | caps18 = 1  | goals18 = 0\n}}\n'''Richard John Huxford''' (born 25 July 1969) is an English former professional [[association football|footballer]] who made more than 200 appearances in [[the Football League]] and the [[Scottish Football League]]. His regular playing position was at [[defender (association football)|right back]], but he also played as a central defender or in [[midfielder|midfield]].\n\n==Playing career==\nHuxford was born in [[Scunthorpe]], [[Lincolnshire]]. As a youngster he joined [[Scunthorpe United F.C.|Scunthorpe United]] as an apprentice, but was released without being offered a full professional contract. He played [[non-league football]] for several years, for clubs including [[Matlock Town F.C.|Matlock Town]],<ref name=Matthews100>{{cite book |last=Matthews |first=Tony |title=Birmingham City: A Complete Record |year=1995 |publisher=Breedon Books |location=Derby |page=100 |isbn=978-1-85983-010-9}}</ref> [[Burton Albion F.C.|Burton Albion]] \u2013 whose manager met [[Gresley F.C.|Gresley Rovers]]' interest in Huxford with a demand for a transfer fee, despite suggesting the player would \"have to improve a great deal\" to find his way into Burton's long-term plans<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.gresleyfc.com/news/article/693 |title=Rovers fail in Huxford bid |newspaper=[[Burton Mail]] |via=Gresley FC Online |date=6 April 1989 |accessdate=28 February 2017}}</ref> \u2013 [[Gainsborough Trinity F.C.|Gainsborough Trinity]],<ref name=Matthews100/> and [[Kettering Town F.C.|Kettering Town]], for whom he played 103 games in all competitions.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.poppiesfans.com/archives/players/?recordID=H37 |title=Player Profile Richard Huxford |website=poppiesfans.com |accessdate=18 October 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120313132454/http://www.poppiesfans.com/archives/players/?recordID=H37 |archivedate=13 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nHe moved into [[the Football League]] with [[Barnet F.C.|Barnet]] in August 1992 in an exchange deal involving [[Dave Tomlinson (footballer)|Dave Tomlinson]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/sport-in-short-football-1539553.html |title=Sport in Short: Football |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |location=London |date=10 August 1992 |accessdate=18 June 2009}}</ref> After 33 league games in the [[1992\u201393 in English football|1992\u201393 season]] as Barnet won the [[Football League Third Division|Division Three]] title,<ref name=NB>{{cite web |url=http://www.neilbrown.newcastlefans.com/player/richardhuxford.html |title=Richard Huxford |website=UK A\u2013Z Transfers |publisher=Neil Brown |accessdate=31 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fchd.info/BARNET.HTM |title=Barnet |website=Football Club History Database |publisher=Richard Rundle |accessdate=18 June 2009}}</ref> Huxford joined [[Football League First Division|Division One]] (second tier) club [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]] on a free transfer.<ref name=Matthews100/> He played 36 games in all competitions in his first season, helping the club reach the play-offs, in which they lost to [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]] in the semifinal.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.millwall-history.co.uk/Millwall-Stats9394-2.htm |title=Millwall Stats 93\u201394 |website=The Millwall History Files |accessdate=18 June 2009}}</ref> During that season he also spent a month on loan at [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] as cover for the injured [[Scott Hiley]].<ref name=Matthews100/>\n\nThe following season, his Millwall career consisted of one three-minute [[substitute (association football)|substitute]] appearance<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.millwall-history.co.uk/Millwall-Stats9495-2.htm |title=Millwall Stats 94\u201395 |website=The Millwall History Files |accessdate=18 June 2009}}</ref> before he went out on another month's loan, this time to [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] of [[Football League Second Division|Division Two]]. The loan was extended for a further two months, then in January 1995 Huxford signed for Bradford City on a permanent basis for a fee of \u00a350,000.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.millwall-history.co.uk/Millwall-Transfers-out.htm |title=Transfer Out |website=The Millwall History Files |accessdate=18 June 2009}}</ref> He contributed to the club's promotion to Division One via the [[Football League One play-offs|play-offs]], and was involved in the build-up to both goals in the [[1996 Football League Second Division play-off Final|play-off final]] against [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/hamilton-engineers-bradfords-elevation-1349367.html |title=Hamilton engineers Bradford's elevation |first=Tim |last=Collings |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |location=London |date=27 May 1996 |accessdate=18 June 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://homepage.ntlworld.com/carousel/ncfc/1996-05-26.html |title=1996-05-26 Bradford City 2 Notts County 0 |website=Up The Maggies |accessdate=18 June 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100421050349/http://homepage.ntlworld.com/carousel/ncfc/1996-05-26.html |archivedate=21 April 2010}}</ref> His chances at Bradford were limited at the higher level, and after a brief spell on loan to [[Peterborough United F.C.|Peterborough United]], the club released him from his contract in January 1997 and he joined [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]], initially on a short-term deal until the end of the season.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.lancashiretelegraph.co.uk/news/6189033.CLARETS__Boss_swoops_for_city_defender_Huxford/ |title=Clarets: Boss swoops for city defender Huxford |newspaper=[[Lancashire Telegraph]] |date=21 January 1997 |accessdate=28 February 2017}}</ref> His contract was extended, and new manager [[Chris Waddle]] put him in the starting eleven,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.lancashiretelegraph.co.uk/news/6173244.CLARETS__Bad_tempered_battle_boils_/ |title=Clarets: Bad-tempered battle boils! |first=Tony |last=Dewhurst |newspaper=[[Lancashire Telegraph]] |date=18 August 1997 |accessdate=28 February 2017}}</ref> but he soon fell out of favour, and was allowed to try his luck in the [[Scottish Football League|Scottish League]], joining [[Dunfermline Athletic F.C.|Dunfermline Athletic]] on loan.\n\nHuxford made his [[Scottish Premier League]] debut on 15 February 1998 away at [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]]: Dunfermline lost 5\u20131.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.lancashiretelegraph.co.uk/news/6159109.CLARETS__Turf_Moor_Notebook/ |title=Clarets: Turf Moor notebook |newspaper=[[Lancashire Telegraph]] |date=28 February 1998 |accessdate=28 February 2017}}</ref> The move was made permanent at the end of the season, and he played fairly regularly in his first permanent season with the club,<ref name=SB1>{{cite web |url=https://www.soccerbase.com/players/player.sd?player_id=3771 |title=Richard Huxford |work=Soccerbase |publisher=Centurycomm |accessdate=31 December 2019}}</ref> but in September 1999 cruciate ligament damage put an end to his Dunfermline career.<ref name=TnA>{{cite news |url=http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/8033022.David_and_Goliath_task_for_City_hero/ |title=David and Goliath task for City hero |newspaper=[[Telegraph & Argus]] |location=Bradford |date=19 January 2002 |accessdate=28 February 2017}}</ref> Released at the end of the [[1999\u20132000 in Scottish football|1999\u20132000 season]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/crawford-to-stay-at-pars-1-461955 |title=Crawford to stay at Pars |first=Desmond |last=Kane |newspaper=[[The Scotsman]] |location=Edinburgh |date=10 May 2000 |accessdate=28 February 2017}}</ref> Huxford signed a one-year contract with part-timers [[Alloa Athletic F.C.|Alloa Athletic]], newly promoted to the [[Scottish Football League First Division|Scottish First Division]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/new-team-to-run-stirling-1-483125 |title=New team to run Stirling |first=Iain |last=Collin |newspaper=[[The Scotsman]] |location=Edinburgh |date=5 August 2000 |accessdate=28 February 2017}}</ref> His season with Alloa was disrupted by injury,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_div_1/1039431.stm |title=Division One preview |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |date=24 November 2000 |accessdate=19 June 2009}}<br>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_div_1/1150814.stm |title=Division One preview |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |date=2 February 2001 |accessdate=19 June 2009}}<br>{{cite news |url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/bankies-on-brink-of-extinction-1-523899 |title=Bankies on brink of extinction |first=Jonathan |last=Coates |newspaper=[[The Scotsman]] |location=Edinburgh |date=1 March 2001 |accessdate=28 February 2017}}</ref> and he was one of numerous players released as the club were relegated.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/a/alloa/1367536.stm |title=Alloa's summer ins and outs |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |date=4 August 2001 |accessdate=19 June 2009}}</ref> [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]] offered a three-month deal at the start of the [[2000\u201301 in Scottish football|2000\u201301 season]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/p/partick_thistle/1367492.stm |title=Thistle's summer ins and outs |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |date=8 June 2001 |accessdate=19 June 2009}}</ref> but when the club decided to go full-time, he made the switch to [[Berwick Rangers F.C.|Berwick Rangers]] in order to continue his studies.<ref name=TnA/> Albeit as a late substitute, he was part of the Berwick team which held [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] to a goalless draw in the [[Scottish Cup]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/2428614/Tennents-Scottish-Cup-Brave-Berwick-earn-replay.html |title=Tennent's Scottish Cup: Brave Berwick earn replay |first=Charles |last=Carrick |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |location=London |date=15 January 2002 |accessdate=31 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2002\u201303 in English football|2002\u201303 season]], Huxford played for [[Cambridge City F.C.|Cambridge City]]'s [[reserve team]] on trial,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cambridgecityfc.com/afolder/Reports/Reserves(a)Haverhill.shtml |title=Reserves miss deserved point |publisher=[[Cambridge City F.C.|Cambridge City]] |accessdate=19 June 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180418032653/http://www.cambridgecityfc.com/afolder/Reports/Reserves(a)Haverhill.shtml |archivedate=18 April 2018}}<br>{{cite web |url=http://www.hamletcroft.co.uk/19-11-02.txt |title=19-11-02 |publisher=[[Haverhill Rovers F.C.]] |accessdate=19 June 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050907133844/http://hamletcroft.co.uk/19-11-02.txt |archivedate=7 September 2005}}</ref> and turned out for [[Ely City F.C.|Ely City]] of the [[Eastern Counties Football League|Eastern Counties League]],<ref name=NB/> while attending courses at a Christian college in [[Hertfordshire]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/IF0502484312/TTDA?u=wikipedia&sid=TTDA&xid=71aed307 |title=Missionaries who are playing ball for Christianity |first=Bess |last=Twiston Davies |newspaper=[[The Times]] |location=London |date=28 December 2002 |page=49 |url-access=subscription}}</ref> Huxford made a return to league football in 2006 with [[Elgin City F.C.|Elgin City]] of the [[Scottish Football League Third Division|Scottish Third Division]], initially as fitness coach, later making one appearance as a player.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AWNB:APJB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=11486690B7967BE8&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB57AB53DF815 |title=Huxford hopes to play part in Elgin revival |newspaper=[[Aberdeen Press & Journal]] |date=30 September 2006 |accessdate=19 June 2009 |via=[[NewsBank]] |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120707105239/http://infoweb.newsbank.com/iw-search/we/InfoWeb?p_action=doc&p_topdoc=1&p_docnum=1&p_sort=YMD_date:D&p_product=AWNB&p_text_direct-0=document_id=(%2011486690B7967BE8%20)&p_docid=11486690B7967BE8&p_theme=aggdocs&p_queryname=11486690B7967BE8&f_openurl=yes&p_nbid=A5FA5FQXMTM0MTY1ODM1MC44MDQ1NzoxOjk6MTI4LjMuMC4w&&p_multi=APJB |archivedate=7 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n==After football==\nWhile playing as a semi-professional in Scotland, Huxford earned a degree in [[sports science]] from the [[University of Edinburgh]].<ref name=TnA/> In 2005, he was appointed as a Sports Science Officer for the [[Scottish Institute of Sport]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sisport.com/sisport/212.html |title=Richard Huxford - Sports Science Officer |publisher=Scottish Institute of Sport |accessdate=18 June 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120224153446/http://www.sisport.com/sisport/212.html |archivedate=24 February 2012}}</ref> Huxford has also coached the youth teams of [[Manchester United F.C. Reserves and Academy|Manchester United]] and [[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]], and the senior squad of American side [[Carolina RailHawks FC|Carolina RailHawks]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.carolinarailhawks.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=553|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708122148/http://www.carolinarailhawks.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=553|url-status=dead|archive-date=8 July 2011|title=Coach Rennie Receives Assistance from Renowned Soccer Specific Sports Scientist|accessdate=18 June 2009|publisher=Carolina RailHawks}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.neilbrown.newcastlefans.com/player/richardhuxford.html League stats] at Neil Brown's ''Post War English & Scottish Football League A\u2013Z Player's Transfer Database''\n*{{soccerbase|id=3771|name=Richard Huxford}}\n*{{soccerbase|id=44361|name=Richard Huxford}} (Elgin City)\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Huxford, Richard}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Scunthorpe]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football fullbacks]]\n[[Category:Scunthorpe United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Matlock Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Burton Albion F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Gainsborough Trinity F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Kettering Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Barnet F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Millwall F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Birmingham City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bradford City A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Peterborough United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Burnley F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Dunfermline Athletic F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Alloa Athletic F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Partick Thistle F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Berwick Rangers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Ely City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Elgin City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:National League (English football) players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football League players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2012}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Richard Huxford\n| image          = Huxford and diallo at railhawks.jpg\n| image_size     = 200\n| caption        = Huxford (left) with [[Hamed Diallo]] during his days coaching at [[Carolina RailHawks]] in April 2009\n| fullname       = Richard John Huxford<ref name=\"Hugman\">{{Hugman|9808|accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref>\n| height         = {{height|ft=5|in=10}}<ref name=SB1/>\n| position       = [[Defender (association football)|Right back]]\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1969|7|25|df=y}}<ref name=\"Hugman\"/>\n| birth_place    = [[Scunthorpe]], England\n| death_date     = \n| youthyears1    = \u2013 \n| youthclubs1    = [[Scunthorpe United F.C.|Scunthorpe United]]\n| years1  = 1987\u20131989 | clubs1  = [[Matlock Town F.C.|Matlock Town]]                          | caps1  =    | goals1  =\n| years2  = 1989      | clubs2  = [[Burton Albion F.C.|Burton Albion]]                        | caps2  =    | goals2  = \n| years3  = 1989\u20131990 | clubs3  = [[Gainsborough Trinity F.C.|Gainsborough Trinity]]          | caps3  =    | goals3  =\n| years4  = 1990\u20131992 | clubs4  = [[Kettering Town F.C.|Kettering Town]]                      | caps4  =    | goals4  = \n| years5  = 1992\u20131993 | clubs5  = [[Barnet F.C.|Barnet]]                                      | caps5  = 33 | goals5  = 1\n| years6  = 1993\u20131995 | clubs6  = [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]]                                  | caps6  = 32 | goals6  = 0\n| years7  = 1994      | clubs7  = \u2192 [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] (loan)           | caps7  = 5  | goals7  = 0\n| years8  = 1994\u20131995 | clubs8  = \u2192 [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] (loan)             | caps8  = 14 | goals8  = 1\n| years9  = 1995\u20131997 | clubs9  = [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]]                      | caps9  = 47 | goals9  = 1\n| years10 = 1996      | clubs10 = \u2192 [[Peterborough United F.C.|Peterborough United]] (loan)   | caps10 = 7  | goals10 = 0\n| years11 = 1997\u20131998 | clubs11 = [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]]                                    | caps11 = 13 | goals11 = 0\n| years12 = 1998      | clubs12 = \u2192 [[Dunfermline Athletic F.C.|Dunfermline Athletic]] (loan) | caps12 = 10 | goals12 = 0\n| years13 = 1998\u20132000 | clubs13 = [[Dunfermline Athletic F.C.|Dunfermline Athletic]]          | caps13 = 27 | goals13 = 1\n| years14 = 2000\u20132001 | clubs14 = [[Alloa Athletic F.C.|Alloa Athletic]]                      | caps14 = 17 | goals14 = 0\n| years15 = 2001      | clubs15 = [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]]                    | caps15 = 6  | goals15 = 0\n| years16 = 2001\u20132002 | clubs16 = [[Berwick Rangers F.C.|Berwick Rangers]]                    | caps16 = 14 | goals16 = 0\n| years17 = 2003      | clubs17 = [[Ely City F.C.|Ely City]]                                  | caps17 = 5  | goals17 = 0\n| years18 = 2006\u20132007 | clubs18 = [[Elgin City F.C.|Elgin City]]                              | caps18 = 1  | goals18 = 0\n}}\n'''Richard John Huxford''' (born 25 July 1969) is an English former professional [[association football|footballer]] who made more than 200 appearances in [[the Football League]] and the [[Scottish Football League]]. His regular playing position was at [[defender (association football)|right back]], but he also played as a central defender or in [[midfielder|midfield]].\n\n==Playing career==\nHuxford was born in [[Scunthorpe]], [[Lincolnshire]]. As a youngster he joined [[Scunthorpe United F.C.|Scunthorpe United]] as an apprentice, but was released without being offered a full professional contract. He played [[non-league football]] for several years, for clubs including [[Matlock Town F.C.|Matlock Town]],<ref name=Matthews100>{{cite book |last=Matthews |first=Tony |title=Birmingham City: A Complete Record |year=1995 |publisher=Breedon Books |location=Derby |page=100 |isbn=978-1-85983-010-9}}</ref> [[Burton Albion F.C.|Burton Albion]] \u2013 whose manager met [[Gresley F.C.|Gresley Rovers]]' interest in Huxford with a demand for a transfer fee, despite suggesting the player would \"have to improve a great deal\" to find his way into Burton's long-term plans<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.gresleyfc.com/news/article/693 |title=Rovers fail in Huxford bid |newspaper=[[Burton Mail]] |via=Gresley FC Online |date=6 April 1989 |accessdate=28 February 2017}}</ref> \u2013 [[Gainsborough Trinity F.C.|Gainsborough Trinity]],<ref name=Matthews100/> and [[Kettering Town F.C.|Kettering Town]], for whom he played 103 games in all competitions.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.poppiesfans.com/archives/players/?recordID=H37 |title=Player Profile Richard Huxford |website=poppiesfans.com |accessdate=18 October 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120313132454/http://www.poppiesfans.com/archives/players/?recordID=H37 |archivedate=13 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nHe moved into [[the Football League]] with [[Barnet F.C.|Barnet]] in August 1992 in an exchange deal involving [[Dave Tomlinson (footballer)|Dave Tomlinson]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/sport-in-short-football-1539553.html |title=Sport in Short: Football |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |location=London |date=10 August 1992 |accessdate=18 June 2009}}</ref> After 33 league games in the [[1992\u201393 in English football|1992\u201393 season]] as Barnet won the [[Football League Third Division|Division Three]] title,<ref name=NB>{{cite web |url=http://www.neilbrown.newcastlefans.com/player/richardhuxford.html |title=Richard Huxford |website=UK A\u2013Z Transfers |publisher=Neil Brown |accessdate=31 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fchd.info/BARNET.HTM |title=Barnet |website=Football Club History Database |publisher=Richard Rundle |accessdate=18 June 2009}}</ref> Huxford joined [[Football League First Division|Division One]] (second tier) club [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]] on a free transfer.<ref name=Matthews100/> He played 36 games in all competitions in his first season, helping the club reach the play-offs, in which they lost to [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]] in the semifinal.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.millwall-history.co.uk/Millwall-Stats9394-2.htm |title=Millwall Stats 93\u201394 |website=The Millwall History Files |accessdate=18 June 2009}}</ref> During that season he also spent a month on loan at [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] as cover for the injured [[Scott Hiley]].<ref name=Matthews100/>\n\nThe following season, his Millwall career consisted of one three-minute [[substitute (association football)|substitute]] appearance<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.millwall-history.co.uk/Millwall-Stats9495-2.htm |title=Millwall Stats 94\u201395 |website=The Millwall History Files |accessdate=18 June 2009}}</ref> before he went out on another month's loan, this time to [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] of [[Football League Second Division|Division Two]]. The loan was extended for a further two months, then in January 1995 Huxford signed for Bradford City on a permanent basis for a fee of \u00a350,000.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.millwall-history.co.uk/Millwall-Transfers-out.htm |title=Transfer Out |website=The Millwall History Files |accessdate=18 June 2009}}</ref> He contributed to the club's promotion to Division One via the [[Football League One play-offs|play-offs]], and was involved in the build-up to both goals in the [[1996 Football League Second Division play-off Final|play-off final]] against [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/hamilton-engineers-bradfords-elevation-1349367.html |title=Hamilton engineers Bradford's elevation |first=Tim |last=Collings |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |location=London |date=27 May 1996 |accessdate=18 June 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://homepage.ntlworld.com/carousel/ncfc/1996-05-26.html |title=1996-05-26 Bradford City 2 Notts County 0 |website=Up The Maggies |accessdate=18 June 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100421050349/http://homepage.ntlworld.com/carousel/ncfc/1996-05-26.html |archivedate=21 April 2010}}</ref> His chances at Bradford were limited at the higher level, and after a brief spell on loan to [[Peterborough United F.C.|Peterborough United]], the club released him from his contract in January 1997 and he joined [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]], initially on a short-term deal until the end of the season.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.lancashiretelegraph.co.uk/news/6189033.CLARETS__Boss_swoops_for_city_defender_Huxford/ |title=Clarets: Boss swoops for city defender Huxford |newspaper=[[Lancashire Telegraph]] |date=21 January 1997 |accessdate=28 February 2017}}</ref> His contract was extended, and new manager [[Chris Waddle]] put him in the starting eleven,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.lancashiretelegraph.co.uk/news/6173244.CLARETS__Bad_tempered_battle_boils_/ |title=Clarets: Bad-tempered battle boils! |first=Tony |last=Dewhurst |newspaper=[[Lancashire Telegraph]] |date=18 August 1997 |accessdate=28 February 2017}}</ref> but he soon fell out of favour, and was allowed to try his luck in the [[Scottish Football League|Scottish League]], joining [[Dunfermline Athletic F.C.|Dunfermline Athletic]] on loan.\n\nHuxford made his [[Scottish Premier League]] debut on 15 February 1998 away at [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]]: Dunfermline lost 5\u20131.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.lancashiretelegraph.co.uk/news/6159109.CLARETS__Turf_Moor_Notebook/ |title=Clarets: Turf Moor notebook |newspaper=[[Lancashire Telegraph]] |date=28 February 1998 |accessdate=28 February 2017}}</ref> The move was made permanent at the end of the season, and he played fairly regularly in his first permanent season with the club,<ref name=SB1>{{cite web |url=https://www.soccerbase.com/players/player.sd?player_id=3771 |title=Richard Huxford |work=Soccerbase |publisher=Centurycomm |accessdate=31 December 2019}}</ref> but in September 1999 cruciate ligament damage put an end to his Dunfermline career.<ref name=TnA>{{cite news |url=http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/8033022.David_and_Goliath_task_for_City_hero/ |title=David and Goliath task for City hero |newspaper=[[Telegraph & Argus]] |location=Bradford |date=19 January 2002 |accessdate=28 February 2017}}</ref> Released at the end of the [[1999\u20132000 in Scottish football|1999\u20132000 season]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/crawford-to-stay-at-pars-1-461955 |title=Crawford to stay at Pars |first=Desmond |last=Kane |newspaper=[[The Scotsman]] |location=Edinburgh |date=10 May 2000 |accessdate=28 February 2017}}</ref> Huxford signed a one-year contract with part-timers [[Alloa Athletic F.C.|Alloa Athletic]], newly promoted to the [[Scottish Football League First Division|Scottish First Division]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/new-team-to-run-stirling-1-483125 |title=New team to run Stirling |first=Iain |last=Collin |newspaper=[[The Scotsman]] |location=Edinburgh |date=5 August 2000 |accessdate=28 February 2017}}</ref> His season with Alloa was disrupted by injury,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_div_1/1039431.stm |title=Division One preview |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |date=24 November 2000 |accessdate=19 June 2009}}<br>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_div_1/1150814.stm |title=Division One preview |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |date=2 February 2001 |accessdate=19 June 2009}}<br>{{cite news |url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/bankies-on-brink-of-extinction-1-523899 |title=Bankies on brink of extinction |first=Jonathan |last=Coates |newspaper=[[The Scotsman]] |location=Edinburgh |date=1 March 2001 |accessdate=28 February 2017}}</ref> and he was one of numerous players released as the club were relegated.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/a/alloa/1367536.stm |title=Alloa's summer ins and outs |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |date=4 August 2001 |accessdate=19 June 2009}}</ref> [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]] offered a three-month deal at the start of the [[2000\u201301 in Scottish football|2000\u201301 season]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/p/partick_thistle/1367492.stm |title=Thistle's summer ins and outs |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |date=8 June 2001 |accessdate=19 June 2009}}</ref> but when the club decided to go full-time, he made the switch to [[Berwick Rangers F.C.|Berwick Rangers]] in order to continue his studies.<ref name=TnA/> Albeit as a late substitute, he was part of the Berwick team which held [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] to a goalless draw in the [[Scottish Cup]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/2428614/Tennents-Scottish-Cup-Brave-Berwick-earn-replay.html |title=Tennent's Scottish Cup: Brave Berwick earn replay |first=Charles |last=Carrick |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |location=London |date=15 January 2002 |accessdate=31 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2002\u201303 in English football|2002\u201303 season]], Huxford played for [[Cambridge City F.C.|Cambridge City]]'s [[reserve team]] on trial,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cambridgecityfc.com/afolder/Reports/Reserves(a)Haverhill.shtml |title=Reserves miss deserved point |publisher=[[Cambridge City F.C.]] |accessdate=19 June 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180418032653/http://www.cambridgecityfc.com/afolder/Reports/Reserves(a)Haverhill.shtml |archivedate=18 April 2018}}<br>{{cite web |url=http://www.hamletcroft.co.uk/19-11-02.txt |title=19-11-02 |publisher=[[Haverhill Rovers F.C.]] |accessdate=19 June 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050907133844/http://hamletcroft.co.uk/19-11-02.txt |archivedate=7 September 2005}}</ref> and turned out for [[Ely City F.C.|Ely City]] of the [[Eastern Counties Football League|Eastern Counties League]],<ref name=NB/> while attending courses at a Christian college in [[Hertfordshire]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/IF0502484312/TTDA?u=wikipedia&sid=TTDA&xid=71aed307 |title=Missionaries who are playing ball for Christianity |first=Bess |last=Twiston Davies |newspaper=[[The Times]] |location=London |date=28 December 2002 |page=49 |url-access=subscription}}</ref> Huxford made a return to league football in 2006 with [[Elgin City F.C.|Elgin City]] of the [[Scottish Football League Third Division|Scottish Third Division]], initially as fitness coach, later making one appearance as a player.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AWNB:APJB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=11486690B7967BE8&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB57AB53DF815 |title=Huxford hopes to play part in Elgin revival |newspaper=[[Aberdeen Press & Journal]] |date=30 September 2006 |accessdate=19 June 2009 |via=[[NewsBank]] |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120707105239/http://infoweb.newsbank.com/iw-search/we/InfoWeb?p_action=doc&p_topdoc=1&p_docnum=1&p_sort=YMD_date:D&p_product=AWNB&p_text_direct-0=document_id=(%2011486690B7967BE8%20)&p_docid=11486690B7967BE8&p_theme=aggdocs&p_queryname=11486690B7967BE8&f_openurl=yes&p_nbid=A5FA5FQXMTM0MTY1ODM1MC44MDQ1NzoxOjk6MTI4LjMuMC4w&&p_multi=APJB |archivedate=7 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n==After football==\nWhile playing as a semi-professional in Scotland, Huxford earned a degree in [[sports science]] from the [[University of Edinburgh]].<ref name=TnA/> In 2005, he was appointed as a Sports Science Officer for the [[Scottish Institute of Sport]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sisport.com/sisport/212.html |title=Richard Huxford - Sports Science Officer |publisher=Scottish Institute of Sport |accessdate=18 June 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120224153446/http://www.sisport.com/sisport/212.html |archivedate=24 February 2012}}</ref> Huxford has also coached the youth teams of [[Manchester United F.C. Reserves and Academy|Manchester United]] and [[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]], and the senior squad of American side [[Carolina RailHawks FC|Carolina RailHawks]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.carolinarailhawks.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=553|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708122148/http://www.carolinarailhawks.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=553|url-status=dead|archive-date=8 July 2011|title=Coach Rennie Receives Assistance from Renowned Soccer Specific Sports Scientist|accessdate=18 June 2009|publisher=Carolina RailHawks}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.neilbrown.newcastlefans.com/player/richardhuxford.html League stats] at Neil Brown's ''Post War English & Scottish Football League A\u2013Z Player's Transfer Database''\n*{{soccerbase|id=3771|name=Richard Huxford}}\n*{{soccerbase|id=44361|name=Richard Huxford}} (Elgin City)\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Huxford, Richard}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Scunthorpe]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football fullbacks]]\n[[Category:Scunthorpe United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Matlock Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Burton Albion F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Gainsborough Trinity F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Kettering Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Barnet F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Millwall F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Birmingham City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bradford City A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Peterborough United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Burnley F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Dunfermline Athletic F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Alloa Athletic F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Partick Thistle F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Berwick Rangers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Ely City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Elgin City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:National League (English football) players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football League players]]\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePlaying career:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richard_Huxford"}
{"title_page": "Robert Lankesheer", "text_new": "'''Robert Lankesheer''' was a stage, radio and television actor, best known for playing the character Leamington Sparr in the radio soap The Dales between 1963<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/66e429e0a2314eb388f5546361818daf|title=Radio Times, 19 September 1963|last=|first=|journal=The Radio Times|date=14 November 1963|issue=2088|pages=33|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and 1966<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/90d6f45577934186bedb47455a8141a3|title=Radio Times, 22 September 1966|last=|first=|journal=The Radio Times|date=15 September 1966|issue=2236|pages=53|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and Chamberlain in [[Doctor Who|Dr Who]] in 1965.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/98ca6bcca44b45b59d6f0d8852f2e46b|title=Radio Times, 3 April 1965|last=|first=|journal=The Radio Times|date=April 1965|issue=2160|pages=8|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nHe was born on April 28, 1914 in Southampton, England. Whilst working for the local government in the land registry department he took evening classes and qualified in law.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Webber, Richard.|title=The complete A-Z of Dad's Army|date=2000|publisher=Orion|others=Perry, Jimmy, 1923-, Croft, David, 1922-2011.|isbn=0-7528-1838-4|location=London|pages=117|oclc=59565472}}</ref> He served in the army during WWII as an officer in the Royal Artillery.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/36318/supplement/158/data.pdf|title=Supplement to the London Gazette, 7 January 1944|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> After the war he decided to take up acting professionally.\n\nOn stage, in addition to his repertory theatre work, Robert Lankesheer played Sir Henry Burke in Templeton at the [[Arts Theatre]] in 1958<ref>{{Cite book|last=Wearing, J. P.|title=The London stage 1950-1959 : a calendar of productions, performers, and personnel|publisher=|year=2014|isbn=978-0-8108-9307-8|edition=Second|location=Lanham|pages=577|oclc=880349749}}</ref> and Mr Quelch in the 1960 and 1961 [[Billy Bunter]] Christmas shows<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.friardale.co.uk/Television%20and%20Radio/Billy%20Bunter%20Shipwrecked%20programme.pdf|title=Billy Bunter Shipwrecked Programme, Victoria Palace Theatre|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.friardale.co.uk/Television%20and%20Radio/Billy%20Bunter's%20Swiss%20Roll%20Programme.pdf|title=Billy Bunter's Swiss Roll, Programme, Victoria Palace Theatre|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> at the Victoria Palace Theatre, London. He had a long association with the [[Royal Opera House|Royal Opera]], Covent Garden, performing roles in Carmen (1973<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rohcollections.org.uk/performance.aspx?performance=17012&row=6|title=Carmen, ROH, 1973|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>), A Midsummer Night's Dream (1974,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rohcollections.org.uk/performance.aspx?page=0&performance=15059&row=9|title=A Midsummer Night's Dream, ROH, 1974|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> 1976,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rohcollections.org.uk/performance.aspx?page=0&performance=15136&row=10|title=A Midsummer Night's Dream, ROH, 1976|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> 1984<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rohcollections.org.uk/performance.aspx?page=0&performance=15832&row=11|title=A Midsummer Night's Dream, ROH, 1984|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>) and Die Zauberfl\u00f6te (1979,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rohcollections.org.uk/performance.aspx?page=0&performance=11937&row=0|title=Die Zauberfl\u00f6te, ROH, 1979|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> 1980,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rohcollections.org.uk/performance.aspx?performance=14400&row=1|title=Die Zauberfl\u00f6te, ROH, 1980|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> 1983,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rohcollections.org.uk/performance.aspx?page=0&performance=14408&row=2|title=Die Zauberfl\u00f6te, ROH, 1983|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> 1985,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rohcollections.org.uk/performance.aspx?page=0&performance=14401&row=3|title=Die Zauberfl\u00f6te, ROH, 1985|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> 1986,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rohcollections.org.uk/performance.aspx?page=0&performance=14402&row=4|title=Die Zauberfl\u00f6te, ROH, 1986|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> 1987,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rohcollections.org.uk/performance.aspx?page=0&performance=16226&row=5|title=Die Zauberfl\u00f6te, ROH, 1987|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> 1989,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rohcollections.org.uk/performance.aspx?page=0&performance=14403&row=6|title=Die Zauberfl\u00f6te, ROH, 1989|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> 1991<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rohcollections.org.uk/performance.aspx?page=0&performance=14404&row=7|title=Die Zauberfl\u00f6te, ROH, 1991|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>). \u00a0\n\nIn films, Robert Lankesheer appeared in David Copperfield<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0065615/fullcredits?ref_=tt_cl_sm#cast|title=David Copperfield, 1970, IMDb|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> (1970) and Young Winston<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0069528/fullcredits/?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm|title=Young Winston, 1972, IMDb|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> (1972)\n\nHis television credits include The Malory Secret<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1663683/?ref_=nv_sr_srsg_1|title=The Mallory Secret, IMDb|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> (1951), At Your Service Ltd<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1673438/fullcredits/?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm|title=At Your Service Ltd., IMDb|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> (1951), The Trial of Andy Fothergill<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1663694/fullcredits/?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm|title=The Trial of Andy Fothergill, IMDb|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> (1951), Emil and the Detectives<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/page/7f71eb494c8144f6a65974f8ccc45960|title=Radio Times, April 18th 1952|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> (1952), Theatre Royal<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0048882/fullcredits/?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm|title=Theatre Royal, IMDb|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> (1955), Tales from Dickens<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0166463/fullcredits/?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm|title=Tales from Dickens, IMDb|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> (1960), Starr and Company<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0165597/fullcredits?ref_=tt_cl_sm#cast|title=Starr and Company, IMDb|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=liv