b|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0054518/fullcredits/?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm|title=The Avengers, IMDb|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> (1963), The Paradise Makers<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0409600/fullcredits/?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm|title=The Paradise Makers, IMDb|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> (1967), Z Cars<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0843225/fullcredits/?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm|title=Z Cars, IMDb|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> (1968, 1976), [[Dad's Army]] (1969<ref>{{Cite book|last=Webber, Richard.|title=The complete A-Z of Dad's Army|date=2000|publisher=Orion|others=Perry, Jimmy, 1923-, Croft, David, 1922-2011.|isbn=0-7528-1838-4|location=London|pages=125|oclc=59565472}}</ref>), ITV Saturday Night Theatre - Rogues Gallery: The Wicked Stage<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0950378/?ref_=ttfc_fc_cl_i736|title=Rogues Gallery: The Wicked Stage, IMDb|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> (1969), Junket 89<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0065926/?ref_=nv_sr_srsg_0|title=Junket 89, IMDb|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> (1970), Bachelor Father<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0162786/fullcredits?ref_=tt_cl_sm#cast|title=Bachelor Father, IMDb|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> (1970), Doctor in Charge<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0068065/fullcredits/?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm|title=Doctor in Charge, IMDb|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> (1972), An Evening with Francis Howerd<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=10 May 1973|title=Radio Times, 14th May 1973|url=https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/7a0071c368944f43897218d561c9eaf6|url-status=live|journal=The Radio Times|issue=2583|pages=27|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> (1973), Thriller<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0164295/fullcredits/?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm|title=Thriller, IMDb|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> (1975), [[The Professionals (TV series)|The Professionals]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0075561/fullcredits/?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm|title=The Professionals, IMDb|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> (1978), [[Fawlty Towers]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0072500/fullcredits/?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm|title=Fawlty Towers, IMDb|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> (1979), Reilly: Ace of Spies<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0085077/fullcredits/?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm|title=Reilly: Ace of Spies, IMDb|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> (1983) and Full House<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0166040/fullcredits/?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm|title=Full House, IMDb|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> (1985).\n\nRobert Lankesheer died on December 29, 1993 in London, England.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0486898/bio?ref_=nm_ov_bio_sm|title=Robert Lankesheer, IMBd|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:English male stage actors]]\n[[Category:English male television actors]]\n", "text_old": "'''Robert Lankesheer''' was a stage, radio and television actor, best known for playing the character Leamington Sparr in the radio soap The Dales between 1963<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/66e429e0a2314eb388f5546361818daf|title=Radio Times, 19 September 1963|last=|first=|journal=The Radio Times|date=14 November 1963|issue=2088|pages=33|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and 1966<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/90d6f45577934186bedb47455a8141a3|title=Radio Times, 22 September 1966|last=|first=|journal=The Radio Times|date=15 September 1966|issue=2236|pages=53|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and Chamberlain in [[Doctor Who|Dr Who]] in 1965.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/98ca6bcca44b45b59d6f0d8852f2e46b|title=Radio Times, 3 April 1965|last=|first=|journal=The Radio Times|date=April 1965|issue=2160|pages=8|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nHe was born on April 28, 1914 in Southampton, England. Whilst working for the local government in the land registry department he took evening classes and qualified in law.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Webber, Richard.|title=The complete A-Z of Dad's Army|date=2000|publisher=Orion|others=Perry, Jimmy, 1923-, Croft, David, 1922-2011.|isbn=0-7528-1838-4|location=London|pages=117|oclc=59565472}}</ref> He served in the army during WWII as an officer in the Royal Artillery.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/36318/supplement/158/data.pdf|title=Supplement to the London Gazette, 7 January 1944|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> After the war he decided to take up acting professionally.\n\nOn stage, in addition to his repertory theatre work, Robert Lankesheer played Sir Henry Burke in Templeton at the [[Arts Theatre]] in 1958<ref>{{Cite book|last=Wearing, J. P.|title=The London stage 1950-1959 : a calendar of productions, performers, and personnel|publisher=|year=2014|isbn=978-0-8108-9307-8|edition=Second|location=Lanham|pages=577|oclc=880349749}}</ref> and Mr Quelch in the 1960 and 1961 [[Billy Bunter]] Christmas shows<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.friardale.co.uk/Television%20and%20Radio/Billy%20Bunter%20Shipwrecked%20programme.pdf|title=Billy Bunter Shipwrecked Programme, Victoria Palace Theatre|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.friardale.co.uk/Television%20and%20Radio/Billy%20Bunter's%20Swiss%20Roll%20Programme.pdf|title=Billy Bunter's Swiss Roll, Programme, Victoria Palace Theatre|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> at the Victoria Palace Theatre, London. He had a long association with the [[Royal Opera House|Royal Opera]], Covent Garden, performing roles in Carmen (1973<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rohcollections.org.uk/performance.aspx?performance=17012&row=6|title=Carmen, ROH, 1973|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>), A Midsummer Night's Dream (1974,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rohcollections.org.uk/performance.aspx?page=0&performance=15059&row=9|title=A Midsummer Night's Dream, ROH, 1974|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> 1976,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rohcollections.org.uk/performance.aspx?page=0&performance=15136&row=10|title=A Midsummer Night's Dream, ROH, 1976|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> 1984<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rohcollections.org.uk/performance.aspx?page=0&performance=15832&row=11|title=A Midsummer Night's Dream, ROH, 1984|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>) and Die Zauberfl\u00f6te (1979,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rohcollections.org.uk/performance.aspx?page=0&performance=11937&row=0|title=Die Zauberfl\u00f6te, ROH, 1979|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> 1980,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rohcollections.org.uk/performance.aspx?performance=14400&row=1|title=Die Zauberfl\u00f6te, ROH, 1980|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> 1983,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rohcollections.org.uk/performance.aspx?page=0&performance=14408&row=2|title=Die Zauberfl\u00f6te, ROH, 1983|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> 1985,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rohcollections.org.uk/performance.aspx?page=0&performance=14401&row=3|title=Die Zauberfl\u00f6te, ROH, 1985|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> 1986,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rohcollections.org.uk/performance.aspx?page=0&performance=14402&row=4|title=Die Zauberfl\u00f6te, ROH, 1986|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> 1987,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rohcollections.org.uk/performance.aspx?page=0&performance=16226&row=5|title=Die Zauberfl\u00f6te, ROH, 1987|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> 1989,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rohcollections.org.uk/performance.aspx?page=0&performance=14403&row=6|title=Die Zauberfl\u00f6te, ROH, 1989|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> 1991<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rohcollections.org.uk/performance.aspx?page=0&performance=14404&row=7|title=Die Zauberfl\u00f6te, ROH, 1991|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>). \u00a0\n\nIn films, Robert Lankesheer appeared in David Copperfield<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0065615/fullcredits?ref_=tt_cl_sm#cast|title=David Copperfield, 1970, IMDb|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> (1970) and Young Winston<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0069528/fullcredits/?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm|title=Young Winston, 1972, IMDb|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> (1972)\n\nHis television credits include The Malory Secret<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1663683/?ref_=nv_sr_srsg_1|title=The Mallory Secret, IMDb|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> (1951), At Your Service Ltd<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1673438/fullcredits/?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm|title=At Your Service Ltd., IMDb|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> (1951), The Trial of Andy Fothergill<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1663694/fullcredits/?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm|title=The Trial of Andy Fothergill, IMDb|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> (1951), Emil and the Detectives (1952<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/page/7f71eb494c8144f6a65974f8ccc45960|title=Radio Times, April 18th 1952|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>), Theatre Royal<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0048882/fullcredits/?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm|title=Theatre Royal, IMDb|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> (1955), Tales from Dickens<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0166463/fullcredits/?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm|title=Tales from Dickens, IMDb|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> (1960), Starr and Company<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0165597/fullcredits?ref_=tt_cl_sm#cast|title=Starr and Company, IMDb|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> (1958), Dancers in Mourning<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0457234/fullcredits/?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm|title=Dancers in Mourning, IMDb|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> (1959), An Arabian Night<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0913952/fullcredits/?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm|title=An Arabian Night, IMDb|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> (1960), Deadline Midnight<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0159863/fullcredits/?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm|title=Deadline Midnight, IMDb|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> (1960), Dixon of Dock Green<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0047728/fullcredits/?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm|title=Dixon of Dock Green, IMDb|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> (1961, 1967), Emergency Ward 10<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0159870/fullcredits/?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm|title=Emergency Ward 10, IMDb|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> (1962),  The Scales of Justice<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0843225/fullcredits/?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm|title=The Scales of Justice, IMDb|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> (1963), Out of This World<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0163475/fullcredits/?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm|title=Out of this World, IMDb|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> (1962), [[Doctor Who|Dr Who]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0056751/fullcredits?ref_=tt_cl_sm#cast|title=Dr Who, IMDb|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> (1965), [[The Avengers (TV series)|The Avengers]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0054518/fullcredits/?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm|title=The Avengers, IMDb|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> (1963), The Paradise Makers<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0409600/fullcredits/?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm|title=The Paradise Makers, IMDb|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> (1967), Z Cars<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0843225/fullcredits/?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm|title=Z Cars, IMDb|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> (1968, 1976), [[Dad's Army]] (1969<ref>{{Cite book|last=Webber, Richard.|title=The complete A-Z of Dad's Army|date=2000|publisher=Orion|others=Perry, Jimmy, 1923-, Croft, David, 1922-2011.|isbn=0-7528-1838-4|location=London|pages=125|oclc=59565472}}</ref>), ITV Saturday Night Theatre - Rogues Gallery: The Wicked Stage<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0950378/?ref_=ttfc_fc_cl_i736|title=Rogues Gallery: The Wicked Stage, IMDb|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> (1969), Junket 89<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0065926/?ref_=nv_sr_srsg_0|title=Junket 89, IMDb|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> (1970), Bachelor Father<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0162786/fullcredits?ref_=tt_cl_sm#cast|title=Bachelor Father, IMDb|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> (1970), Doctor in Charge<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0068065/fullcredits/?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm|title=Doctor in Charge, IMDb|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> (1972), An Evening with Francis Howerd (1973<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/7a0071c368944f43897218d561c9eaf6|title=Radio Times, 14th May 1973|last=|first=|journal=The Radio Times|date=10 May 1973|issue=2583|pages=27|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>), Thriller<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0164295/fullcredits/?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm|title=Thriller, IMDb|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> (1975), [[The Professionals (TV series)|The Professionals]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0075561/fullcredits/?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm|title=The Professionals, IMDb|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> (1978), [[Fawlty Towers]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0072500/fullcredits/?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm|title=Fawlty Towers, IMDb|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> (1979), Reilly: Ace of Spies<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0085077/fullcredits/?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm|title=Reilly: Ace of Spies, IMDb|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> (1983) and Full House<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0166040/fullcredits/?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm|title=Full House, IMDb|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> (1985).\n\nRobert Lankesheer died on December 29, 1993 in London, England.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0486898/bio?ref_=nm_ov_bio_sm|title=Robert Lankesheer, IMBd|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:English male stage actors]]\n[[Category:English male television actors]]\n", "name_user": "Homer Perly", "label": "safe", "comment": "Citations", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_Lankesheer"}
{"title_page": "Marly Youmans", "text_new": "{{infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] --> \n|name=Marly Youmans\n|image=Marlyyoumans.jpg\n|imagesize=320\n|alt= \n|caption=Marly Youmans on a panel of \"Poets Who Write Other Genres\" at the 2012 [[:en:West Chester University Poetry Conference|West Chester University Poetry Conference]]\n|pseudonym=\n|birth_name=Susan Marlene Youmans\n|birth_date= {{Birth date and age|1953|11|22}}\n|birth_place= Aiken, South Carolina\n|death_date= \n|death_place= \n|resting_place= \n|occupation= poet, novelist, and short story writer\n|language= English\n|nationality= American\n|ethnicity= \n|citizenship= \n|education= \n|alma_mater=\n|period= \n|genre= poetry, novels, short stories, books for children\n|subject= \n|movement= [[New Formalism]]\n|notableworks= \n|spouse=\n|partner= \n|children=\n|relatives= \n|influences=\n|influenced= \n|awards=\n|signature= \n|signature_alt= \n|website= {{URL|www.thepalaceat2.blogspot.com}}\n|portaldisp= \n}}\n'''Marly Youmans''' (born '''Susan Marlene Youmans'''; November 22, 1953 in [[Aiken, South Carolina]]) is an American poet, novelist and short story writer. Her work reflects certain recurring themes such as nature, magic, faith and redemption, and often references visual art.\n\n== Background ==\nMarly Youmans grew up in [[Louisiana]], [[North Carolina]], and elsewhere. She currently lives in the village of [[Cooperstown, New York]], with her husband and three children. She graduated from [[Hollins College]], [[Brown University]], and [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]].  She taught at [[State University of New York]] but quit academia after receiving promotion and tenure in her fifth year.<ref>{{cite book| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xxd451POnpYC&pg=PT485&dq=Marly+Youmans&cd=5#v=onepage&q=Marly%20Youmans&f=false| title=Southern writers: a new biographical dictionary| editors=Joseph M. Flora, Amber Vogel, Bryan Albin Giemza| publisher=LSU Press| year= 2006| isbn=978-0-8071-3123-7 }}</ref>\n\n== Writing ==\nHer published work consists of five books of poetry, eight novels and two fantasies for young readers, as well as uncollected short stories, essays and poems. Across all these idioms, her work displays a commitment to rhythm, the sound of words, imagery and complexity of form and allusion. ''Thaliad'', for example, is an epic poem that tells a compelling story of children who survive an apocalypse to begin a new society, written as though a spoken history remembranced in blank verse a generation on. Her novels have been described as 'literary fiction at its finest' in ''Books and Culture''<ref>[http://www.booksandculture.com/articles/webexclusives/2012/may/whitecamellia.html Linda McCullough Moore, Books and Culture, May 2012]</ref> while ''The Advocate'' has cited her skill at mastering poetic forms.<ref>[http://theadvocate.com/utility/homepagestories/4857392-129/poets-invite-readers-to-share Greg Langley, ''The Advocate'', 30 January 2013]</ref> The editor of Books and Culture says, \"Youmans (pronounced like 'yeoman' with an 's' added) is the best-kept secret among contemporary American writers.\"<ref>{{Cite web|title = The Top Ten Books of 2003|url = http://www.booksandculture.com/articles/webexclusives/2003/december/031222.html|website = Books and Culture|access-date = 2016-01-29}}</ref>\n\nHer books demonstrate a number of continuing interests: in lives lived close to nature, whether in the past (''Catherwood'') or the future (''Thaliad''), magic, faith and redemption (''Val/Orson'', ''The Foliate Head'') and the individual\u2019s journey from youth to adulthood (''Inglewood'', ''A Death at the White Camelia Orphanage''). Visual art is often referenced in her work and ''Charis in the World of Wonders,'' ''The Book of the Red King,'' ''Thaliad,'' ''The Foliate Head, Glimmerglass, and Maze of Blood'' were collaborations with the artist [[Clive Hicks-Jenkins]] with decorations throughout the texts. She provided the title poems for an illustrated anthology, ''The Book of Ystwyth: Six Poets on the Art of Clive Hicks-Jenkins''.<ref>Bonta, Dave, Callum James, Andrea Selch, Catriona Urquhart, Damian Walford Davies and Marly Youmans, ''The Book of Ystwyth: Six Poets on the Art of Clive Hicks-Jenkins'' (2011: Carolina Wren Press) {{ISBN|978-0-932112-89-7}}\n</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\nYoumans has been awarded many \"book of the year\" and \"best of the year\" citations by magazines, newspapers, and organizations. She is the winner of [[The Michael Shaara Award for Excellence in Civil War Fiction]] for ''The Wolf Pit'',<ref>{{cite news |title=SON'S PASSION FOR CIVIL WAR LED HER TO WRITE AWARD-WINNING BOOK |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=SL&p_theme=sl&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0F46E0A49BD671B3&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |work=[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]] |date=June 26, 2002 |accessdate=2008-09-18 }}</ref> her third novel, which was also on the short list for The Southern Book Award.  She is a two-time winner of the Theodore Hoepfner Award for the short story and the winner of the New Writers Award of ''Capital Magazine'' (New York), also for the short story. Her latest awards are [[The Ferrol Sams Award for Fiction]] and the Silver in fiction, [[Www.indiefab.forewordreviews.com/winners/2012/general|ForeWord BOTYA Awards]] for ''A Death at the White Camellia Orphanage'' (Mercer University Press, 2012.) ''Glimmerglass'' and ''Maze of Blood'' were ForeWord BOTYA finalists. She has held fellowships from Yaddo, New York State, and elsewhere.\n\nShe was a judge of the 2012 National Book Awards.<ref>[https://www.nationalbook.org/awards-prizes/national-book-awards-2012#.UQ7Xiu37VT4 National Book Awards 2012]</ref>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n\n=== Novels ===\n* ''Little Jordan'' (Boston: David R. Godine, 1995) {{ISBN|978-1-56792-029-1}} (reprint Tempest, 1996)\n* {{cite book| title=Catherwood| publisher=New York: Farrar, Straus & Giroux| year=1996| isbn=978-0-374-11972-0| url=https://archive.org/details/catherwood00youm}} (reprint Bard 1997)\n* {{cite book| title=The Wolf Pit| publisher=New York: Farrar, Straus & Giroux| year=2001| isbn=978-0-374-29195-2| url=https://archive.org/details/wolfpit00youm}}   (reprint Harcourt, 2003, {{ISBN|978-0-15-602714-4}}) \n* ''Val/Orson'' (Hornsea, UK: P. S. Publishing, 2009)  1-906301-51-4 / 9781906301514 (UK) [https://web.archive.org/web/20080220211708/http://store.pspublishing.co.uk/ dual jacketed/unjacketed limited editions]\n*''A Death at the White Camellia Orphanage'' (Macon: Mercer University Press, 2012) 0881462713 / 9780881462715 (hardcover/paperback/ebook)\n*''Glimmerglass'' (Macon: Mercer University Press, 2014) {{ISBN|978-0881464917}} (hardcover)\n*''Maze of Blood'' (Macon: Mercer University Press, 2015) {{ISBN|978-0881465365}} (hardcover)\n*''Charis in the World of Wonders'' (San Francisco: Ignatius Press, 2020){{ISBN|978-1621643043}} (Sythe-sewn softbound with French flaps)\n\n=== Poetry ===\n*''The Book of the Red King'' (Montreal: Phoenicia Publishing, 2019) {{ISBN| 978-1-927496-15-2}} {{ISBN| 978-1-927496-14-5}} (dual hard/softcover)\n*''Thaliad'' (Montreal, CA: Phoenicia Publishing, 2012) {{ISBN|978-0-9866909-3-8}} (dual hard/softcover)\n*''The Foliate Head'' (UK: Stanza Press, 2012) {{ISBN|978-1-848634-60-2}}\n* ''The Throne of Psyche'' (Mercer University Press - Poetry, 2011) {{ISBN|0881462322}} {{ISBN|9780881462326}} (dual hard/softcover)\n* ''Claire: poems'' (Louisiana State University, 2003), {{ISBN|0-8071-2901-1}} (dual hard/softcover)\n\n=== Books for young adults ===\n* {{cite book| title=The Curse of the Raven Mocker| publisher=Farrar, Straus & Giroux| year=2003| isbn=978-0-374-31667-9| url-access=registration| url=https://archive.org/details/curseofravenmock0000youm}} (reprint Firebird) \n* {{cite book| title=Ingledove| url=https://archive.org/details/ingledove00youm| url-access=registration| publisher=Farrar, Straus & Giroux| year= 2005| isbn= 978-0-374-33599-1 }}  (reprint Firebird, 2006, {{ISBN|978-0-14-240704-2}})\n\n=== Essays ===\n* 'Fire in the Labyrinth' in Simon Callow, Andrew Green, Rex Harley, Clive Hicks-Jenkins, Kathe Koja, Anita Mills, Montserrat Prat, Jacqueline Thalmann, Damian Walford Davies and Marly Youmans, ''Clive Hicks-Jenkins'' (2011: Lund Humphries) {{ISBN|978-1-84822-082-9}}, pp.&nbsp;99\u2013123\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Reviews==\n* Matthew Gilbert, [[Www.articles.sun-sentinel.com/1995-12-31/entertainment/9512260250 1 meg-jordan-body|\"Lyrical Prose for a Coming of Age\" (''Little Jordan''), ''The Boston Globe'']], December 31, 1995\n* Philip Gambone, [[Www.nytimes.com/1996/05/26/books/books-in-brief-fiction-another-part-of-the-forest.html|\"Another Part of the Forest\" (review of ''Catherwood), The New York Times Book Review,'']] May 26, 1996\n* Paula Friedman, [[Www.washingtonpost.com/archive/entertainment/books/1997/09/14/fiction/2d217c13-b6e3-aeb2-c9e6e17e5777/|\"Fiction\" (''Catherwood'') in The Washington Post]], September 14, 1997\n* Fred Chappell, \"''Catherwood'',\" ''The Raleigh News and Observer,'' June 23, 1996\n* Catherwood in ''[[Www.ew.com/gallery/10-most-criminally-underrated-books|Entertainment Weekly]]'', March 14, 2014\n* Bob Summer, [[Articles.orlandosentinel.com/2002-02-10/news/0202080456 1 novel-youmans-wolf-pit|\"Novel of Civil War Soldier and Slave Transcends Genre\" (''The Wolf Pit''), ''The Orlando Sentinel,'']] February 10, 2002\n* \"The Wolf Pit\" [[Www.publishersweekly.com/978-0-374-29195-2|(starred review) at ''Publishers Weekly'']], 2001\n* John Wilson, [[Www.booksandculture/articles/webexclusives/2003/december/031222.html|\"The Top Ten Books of 2003\" (''The Curse of the Raven Mocker''), ''Books and Culture Magazine'']], December 2003\n* Greg Langley, Books Editor, \"YA titles include very good books\" (''Ingledove'', Best YA Fiction of 2005, ''TBRA'') ''The 