fiction/author-spotlight-marly-youmans/|\"Author Spotlight: Marly Youmans, ''Lightspeed,'']] February 2013\n*[http://clarkesworldmagazine.com/youmans_interview/ Interview] at ''[[Clarkesworld Magazine]]'', May 2010\n*Interview, [[Www.cwbr.com/civilwarbookreview/index.php?q=2299&field=ID&browse=yes&record=full&searching=yes&Submit=Search|\"Marly Youmans discussed her novel, 'The Wolf Pit,'\" ''Civil War Book Review'']], Fall 2002\n*{{cite news| title=Another Part of the Forest| url= https://www.nytimes.com/books/97/09/07/nnp/19634.html| date=May 26, 1996| author= [[Philip Gambone]]| work=The New York Times}}\n* {{isfdb name}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Youmans, Marly}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:American women novelists]]\n[[Category:American women short story writers]]\n[[Category:People from Aiken, South Carolina]]\n[[Category:American women poets]]\n[[Category:Hollins University alumni]]\n[[Category:Brown University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill alumni]]\n[[Category:State University of New York faculty]]\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century American poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century American short story writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American short story writers]]\n[[Category:Novelists from New York (state)]]\n", "name_user": "Tobias Smollett", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBibliography", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marly_Youmans"}
{"title_page": "1976 Summer Paralympics", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{See also|1976 Summer Olympics}}\n{{Infobox Olympic games|1976|Summer|Paralympics|\n| image       = Torontolympiad 1976.jpg\n| host_city   = [[Toronto]], Canada\n| nations     = 41\n| athletes    = 1,657 (1,404 men, 253 women)\n| events      = 447 in 13 [[Paralympic sports|sports]]\n| opened_by   = [[Lieutenant Governor of Ontario|Lieutenant Governor]] [[Pauline Mills McGibbon|Pauline McGibbon]]\n| opening     = 4 August\n| closing     = 12 August\n| stadium     = [[Woodbine Racetrack]]<br />[[Centennial Park Stadium]]\n| summer_prev = [[1972 Summer Paralympics|Heidelberg 1972]]\n| summer_next = [[1980 Summer Paralympics|Arnhem 1980]]\n| winter_prev = [[1976 Winter Paralympics|\u00d6rnsk\u00f6ldsvik 1976]]\n| winter_next = [[1980 Winter Paralympics|Geilo 1980]]\n}}\n\nThe '''1976 Summer Paralympics''' ({{lang-fr|Les V<sup>\u00e8me</sup> Paralympiques d'\u00e9t\u00e9}}), branded as '''Torontolympiad \u2013 1976 Olympiad for the Physically Disabled''', was the fifth [[Paralympic Games]] to be held. They were hosted by [[Toronto]], [[Canada]], from 4 to 12 August 1976, marking the first time a Paralympics was held in Americas and in Canada. The games began three days after the close of the [[1976 Summer Olympics]] in [[Montreal]].\n\n==Context==\nThis was the first time global politics interfered with the Paralympic Games. \"The problem stemmed from the logic that admitting a team from South Africa was to give implicit approval for its [[Apartheid in South Africa|government's attitude]] towards segregation and racism.\" Although the South African team at the time was a multi-racial one, the Canadian government withdrew its half million dollar contribution and \"matching amounts of funds were likely to be pulled out by the metropolitan government\".<ref name=\"Bailey\">{{Cite book| last=Bailey | first=Steve | title=Athlete First: A history of the paralympic movement | publication-date=2008 | publisher=John Wiley & Sons | pages=35\u201336 | isbn=9780470058244}}</ref> The provincial government at Queen's Park eventually covered the tab.<ref name=\"torontoist.com\">http://torontoist.com/2014/06/historicist-torontolympiad-76/</ref>\n\nTwo groups, both with the same President - [[Ludwig Guttmann]] - were involved in the decision-making: the [[International Sports Organisation for the Disabled]] and the [[International Stoke Mandeville Games Federation]]. Guttman and Bob Jackson, (Chairman of the Organising Committee) worked to convince the governments to honour their promises of support and were largely successful. Nevertheless, a number of teams withdrew, following on from the Montreal boycott by 25 countries, and were threatened with exclusion from future events. Later, efforts were made to develop a joint policy with the [[International Olympic Committee]].<ref name=\"Bailey\" />\n\n[[Rhodesia at the Paralympics|Rhodesia]] was not allowed to participate as the Canadian government refused to grant visas for the Rhodesian Paralympic team to attend the competition.<ref name=Pathways>{{cite journal|last=Little|first=Cliff|title=The Paralympic Protest Paradox: The Politics of Rhodesian Participation in the Paralympic Games, 1960\u20131980|journal=Pathways: Critiques and Discourse in Olympic Research|year=2008|url=http://www.la84foundation.org/SportsLibrary/ISOR/isor2008p.pdf|accessdate=18 May 2011|pages=123\u2013131|format=Pdf}}</ref>\n\n==Venues==\n\nThe opening of the 1976 games was held at [[Woodbine Race Track]] in north [[Etobicoke]]. There was no athletes' village, so competitors were housed at [[York University]] (Keele campus), [[University of Toronto]] (St. George Campus), and the [[CNIB]] (national headquarters in Toronto).<ref name=\"torontoist.com\"/> Israeli athletes were housed at an undisclosed hotel due to security concerns.<ref name=\"torontoist.com\"/> Closing ceremonies and outdoor events (mainly [[track and field]]) took place at [[Centennial Park Stadium]]. [[Centennial Park (Toronto)|Centennial Gymnasium]] and [[Centennial Park (Toronto)|Centennial Park's Olympic Pool (Etobicoke Olympium)]] were the other venues (for indoor and swimming events respectively).\n\n==Media coverage==\n\nThe 1976 games marked the first television coverage of Paralympic events. Performances were shown to viewers in [[Southern Ontario]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Untitled|work=Toronotolympiad|date=4 August 1976}}</ref>\nWithin the Toronto area, a consortium of local cable companies (including [[CUC Broadcasting|Trillium Cable]] and [[Rogers Cable]]) carried the games on channel 10 after CTV and Global TV declined to carry them.<ref name=\"torontoist.com\"/>\n\n==Sports==\nAt the 1976 games, [[amputee]]s and [[visually impaired]] athletes competed for the first time; previous editions of the Paralympic Games had included only [[wheelchair]] athletes. Within the sport of [[athletics (sport)|athletics]], new wheelchair racing distances of 200 m, 400 m, 800 m and 1500 m were added. [[Sport shooting|Shooting]] and [[goalball]], both previously [[demonstration sport|demonstration events]], were included as official medal sports.<ref>{{cite web |title=Toronto 1976 |publisher=[[International Paralympic Committee]] |year=2008 |url=http://www.paralympic.org/toronto-1976|accessdate=2015-03-12 }}</ref>\n\n* [[Archery at the 1976 Summer Paralympics|Archery]]\n* [[Athletics at the 1976 Summer Paralympics|Athletics]]\n* [[Dartchery at the 1976 Summer Paralympics|Dartchery]]\n* [[Goalball at the 1976 Summer Paralympics|Goalball]]\n* [[Lawn bowls at the 1976 Summer Paralympics|Lawn bowls]]\n* [[Shooting at the 1976 Summer Paralympics|Shooting]]\n* [[Snooker at the 1976 Summer Paralympics|Snooker]]\n* [[Swimming at the 1976 Summer Paralympics|Swimming]]\n* [[Table tennis at the 1976 Summer Paralympics|Table tennis]]\n* [[Volleyball at the 1976 Summer Paralympics|Volleyball]]\n* [[Weightlifting at the 1976 Summer Paralympics|Weightlifting]]\n* [[Wheelchair basketball at the 1976 Summer Paralympics|Wheelchair basketball]]\n* [[Wheelchair fencing at the 1976 Summer Paralympics|Wheelchair fencing]]\n\n== Medal table ==\n{{Main|1976 Summer Paralympics medal table}}\nThe top 10 [[National Paralympic Committee|NPCs]] by number of gold medals are listed below. The host nation, Canada, is highlighted.\n{{Medals table\n | caption        = \n | host           = \n | flag_template  = FlagIPC\n | event          = 1976 Summer\n | team           = \n | gold_USA = 66 | silver_USA = 44 | bronze_USA = 45\n | gold_NED = 45 | silver_NED = 25 | bronze_NED = 14\n | gold_ISR = 40 | silver_ISR = 13 | bronze_ISR = 16\n | gold_FRG = 37 | silver_FRG = 34 | bronze_FRG = 26\n | gold_GBR = 29 | silver_GBR = 29 | bronze_GBR = 36\n | gold_CAN = 25 | silver_CAN = 26 | bronze_CAN = 26 | host_CAN = yes \n | gold_POL = 24 | silver_POL = 17 | bronze_POL = 12\n | gold_FRA = 23 | silver_FRA = 21 | bronze_FRA = 14\n | gold_SWE = 22 | silver_SWE = 27 | bronze_SWE = 24\n | gold_AUT = 17 | silver_AUT = 16 | bronze_AUT = 17\n}}\n\n== Participating delegations ==\nForty-one delegations took part in the Toronto Paralympics. [[Burma at the 1976 Summer Paralympics|Burma]], [[Colombia at the 1976 Summer Paralympics|Colombia]], [[Ecuador at the 1976 Summer Paralympics|Ecuador]], [[Greece at the 1976 Summer Paralympics|Greece]], [[Guatemala at the 1976 Summer Paralympics|Guatemala]], [[Indonesia at the 1976 Summer Paralympics|Indonesia]] and [[Luxembourg at the 1976 Summer Paralympics|Luxembourg]] made their first appearances.<ref>{{cite web |title= Medal Standings \u2013 Toronto 1976 Paralympic Games |publisher=[[International Paralympic Committee]] |year=2008 |url=http://www.paralympic.org/Sport/Results/reports.html?type=medalstandings&games=1976PG&sport=all |accessdate=2008-08-08}}</ref>\n\n[[South Africa at the Paralympics|South Africa]] was competing at the Paralympics for the fourth time. Although banned from the Olympic Games due to its policy of [[apartheid]], it was not banned from the Paralympics until 1980, and Canada, as host country, did not object to its participation. These were, however, to be its last Paralympics before the dismantling of apartheid; The [[Netherlands]], as hosts of the [[1980 Summer Paralympics|1980 Games]], declared South Africa's further participation \"undesirable\".<ref>[http://www.iisg.nl/collections/anti-apartheid/history/jaren70-5.php \"'The Netherlands against Apartheid' \u2013 1970s\"], International Institute of Social History</ref><ref>[http://www.paralympic.org/Sport/Results/search.html?npc=RSA&gender=all&medal=all&sport=all&games=all South Africa at the Paralympics], [[International Paralympic Committee]]</ref>\n{{clear}}\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-3}}\n* {{FlagIPC|ARG|1976 Summer|20}}\n* {{FlagIPC|AUS|1976 Summer|46}}\n* {{FlagIPC|AUT|1976 Summer|42}}\n* {{FlagIPC|BAH|1976 Summer|6}}\n* {{FlagIPC|BEL|1976 Summer|45}}\n* {{FlagIPC|BRA|1976 Summer|23}}\n* {{FlagIPC|BIR|1976 Summer|4}}\n* {{FlagIPC|CAN|1976 Summer|89}}\n* {{FlagIPC|COL|1976 Summer|11}}\n* {{FlagIPC|DEN|1976 Summer|21}}\n* {{FlagIPC|ECU|1976 Summer|3}}\n* {{FlagIPC|EGY|1976 Summer|27}}\n* {{FlagIPC|ETH|1976 Summer|1}}\n* {{FlagIPC|FIJ|1976 Summer|9}}\n{{Col-3}}\n* {{FlagIPC|FIN|1976 Summer|50}}\n* {{FlagIPC|FRA|1976 Summer|52}}\n* {{FlagIPC|GBR|1976 Summer|87}}\n* {{FlagIPC|GRE|1976 Summer|3}}\n* {{FlagIPC|GUA|1976 Summer|11}}\n* {{FlagIPC|HKG|1976 Summer|11}}\n* {{FlagIPC|HUN|1976 Summer|2}} \n* {{FlagIPC|INA|1976 Summer|12}}\n* {{FlagIPC|IRL|1976 Summer|19}}\n* {{FlagIPC|ISR|1976 Summer|59}}\n* {{FlagIPC|ITA|1976 Summer|24}}\n* {{FlagIPC|JPN|1976 Summer|34}}\n* {{FlagIPC|LUX|1976 Summer|3}}\n* {{FlagIPC|MEX|1976 Summer|32}}\n{{Col-3}}\n* {{FlagIPC|NED|1976 Summer|58}}\n* {{FlagIPC|NZL|1976 Summer|12}}\n* {{FlagIPC|NOR|1976 Summer|41}}\n* {{FlagIPC|PER|1976 Summer|2}}\n* {{FlagIPC|POL|1976 Summer|37}}\n* {{FlagIPC|RSA|1976 Summer|37}}\n* {{FlagIPC|KOR|1976 Summer|7}}\n* {{FlagIPC|ESP|1976 Summer|22}}\n* {{FlagIPC|SWE|1976 Summer|69}}\n* {{FlagIPC|SUI|1976 Summer|49}}\n* {{FlagIPC|UGA|1976 Summer|1}}\n* {{FlagIPC|USA|1976 Summer|97}}\n* {{FlagIPC|FRG|1976 Summer|93}}\n{{Col-end}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Sports}}\n* [[Canada at the Paralympics]]\n* World Paralympiads in Canada\n** 1976 Summer Paralympics \u2013 [[Toronto]]\n** [[2010 Winter Paralympics]] \u2013 [[Vancouver]]\u2014[[Whistler, British Columbia|Whistler]]\n* [[1976 Winter Paralympics]]\n* [[1976 Summer Olympics]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box\n| title = ''[[Summer Paralympic Games|Summer Paralympics]]'' <br />[[Toronto]]\n| before = [[1972 Summer Paralympics|Heidelberg]]\n| after = [[1980 Summer Paralympics|Arnhem]]\n| years = ''V Paralympic Summer Games'' (1976)\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Paralympic Games}}\n\n[[Category:1976 Summer Olympics|Paralympic]]\n[[Category:1976 in Canadian sports|Paralympics, 1976]]\n[[Category:1976 Summer Paralympics|*]]\n[[Category:International sports competitions hosted by Canada|Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Multi-sport events in Canada]]\n[[Category:1976 in multi-sport events|Paralympic Games]]\n[[Category:Summer Paralympic Games]]\n[[Category:1976 in Toronto|Paralympic Games]]\n[[Category:August 1976 sports events in Canada]]\n[[Category:International sports competitions in Toronto]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{See also|1976 Summer Olympics}}\n{{Infobox Olympic games|1976|Summer|Paralympics|\n| image       = Torontolympiad 1976.jpg\n| host_city   = [[Toronto]], Canada\n| nations     = 41\n| athletes    = 1,657 (1,404 men, 253 women)\n| events      = 447 in 13 [[Paralympic sports|sports]]\n| opened_by   = [[Lieutenant Governor of Ontario|Lieutenant Governor]] [[Pauline Mills McGibbon|Pauline McGibbon]]\n| opening     = 4 August\n| closing     = 12 August\n| stadium     = [[Woodbine Racetrack]]<br />[[Centennial Park Stadium]]\n| summer_prev = [[1972 Summer Paralympics|Heidelberg 1972]]\n| summer_next = [[1980 Summer Paralympics|Arnhem 1980]]\n| winter_prev = [[1976 Winter Paralympics|\u00d6rnsk\u00f6ldsvik 1976]]\n| winter_next = [[1980 Winter Paralympics|Geilo 1980]]\n}}\n\nThe '''1976 Summer Paralympics''' ({{lang-fr|Les V<sup>\u00e8me</sup> Paralympiques d'\u00e9t\u00e9}}), branded as '''Torontolympiad \u2013 1976 Olympiad for the Physically Disabled''', was the fifth [[Paralympic Games]] to be held. They were hosted by [[Toronto]], [[Canada]], from 4 to 12 August 1976, marking the first time a Paralympics was held in Americas and in Canada. The games began three days after the close of the [[1976 Summer Olympics]] in [[Montreal]].\n\n==Context==\nThis was the first time global politics interfered with the Paralympic Games. \"The problem stemmed from the logic that admitting a team from South Africa was to give implicit approval for its [[Apartheid in South Africa|government's attitude]] towards segregation and racism.\" Although the South African team at the time was a multi-racial one, the Canadian government withdrew its half million dollar contribution and \"matching amounts of funds were likely to be pulled out by the metropolitan government\".<ref name=\"Bailey\">{{Cite book| last=Bailey | first=Steve | title=Athlete First: A history of the paralympic movement | publication-date=2008 | publisher=John Wiley & Sons | pages=35\u201336 | isbn=9780470058244}}</ref> The provincial government at Queen's Park eventually covered the tab.<ref name=\"torontoist.com\">http://torontoist.com/2014/06/historicist-torontolympiad-76/</ref>\n\nTwo groups, both with the same President - [[Ludwig Guttmann]] - were involved in the decision-making: the [[International Sports Organisation for the Disabled]] and the [[International Stoke Mandeville Games Federation]]. Guttman and Bob Jackson, (Chairman of the Organising Committee) worked to convince the governments to honour their promises of support and were largely successful. Nevertheless, a number of teams withdrew, following on from the Montreal boycott by 25 countries, and were threatened with exclusion from future events. Later, efforts were made to develop a joint policy with the [[International Olympic Committee]].<ref name=\"Bailey\" />\n\n[[Rhodesia at the Paralympics|Rhodesia]] was not allowed to participate as the Canadian government refused to grant visas for the Rhodesian Paralympic team to attend the competition.<ref name=Pathways>{{cite journal|last=Little|first=Cliff|title=The Paralympic Protest Paradox: The Politics of Rhodesian Participation in the Paralympic Games, 1960\u20131980|journal=Pathways: Critiques and Discourse in Olympic Research|year=2008|url=http://www.la84foundation.org/SportsLibrary/ISOR/isor2008p.pdf|accessdate=18 May 2011|pages=123\u2013131|format=Pdf}}</ref>\n\n==Venues==\n\nThe opening of the 1976 games was held at [[Woodbine Race Track]] in north [[Etobicoke]]. There was no athletes' village, so competitors were housed at [[York University]] (Keele campus), [[University of Toronto]] (St. George Campus), and the [[CNIB]] (national headquarters in Toronto).<ref name=\"torontoist.com\"/> Israeli athletes were housed at an undisclosed hotel due to security concerns.<ref name=\"torontoist.com\"/> Closing ceremonies and outdoor events (mainly [[track and field]]) took place at [[Centennial Park Stadium]]. [[Centennial Park (Toronto)|Centennial Gymnasium]] and [[Centennial Park (Toronto)|Centennial Park's Olympic Pool (Etobicoke Olympium)]] were the other venues (for indoor and swimming events respectively).\n\n==Media coverage==\n\nThe 1976 games marked the first television coverage of Paralympic events. Performances were shown to viewers in [[Southern Ontario]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Untitled|work=Toronotolympiad|date=4 August 1976}}</ref>\nWithin the Toronto area, a consortium of local cable companies (including [[CUC Broadcasting|Trillium Cable]] and [[Rogers Cable]]) carried the games on channel 10 after CTV and Global TV declined to carry them.<ref name=\"torontoist.com\"/>\n\n==Sports==\nAt the 1976 games, [[amputee]]s and [[visually impaired]] athletes competed for the first time; previous editions of the Paralympic Games had included only [[wheelchair]] athletes. Within the sport of [[athletics (sport)|athletics]], new wheelchair racing distances of 200 m, 400 m, 800 m and 1500 m were added. [[Sport shooting|Shooting]] and [[goalball]], both previously [[demonstration sport|demonstration events]], were included as official medal sports.<ref>{{cite web |title=Toronto 1976 |publisher=[[International Paralympic Committee]] |year=2008 |url=http://www.paralympic.org/toronto-1976|accessdate=2015-03-12 }}</ref>\n\n* [[Archery at the 1976 Summer Paralympics|Archery]]\n* [[Athletics at the 1976 Summer Paralympics|Athletics]]\n* [[Dartchery at the 1976 Summer Paralympics|Dartchery]]\n* [[Goalball at the 1976 Summer Paralympics|Goalball]]\n* [[Lawn bowls at the 1976 Summer Paralympics|Lawn bowls]]\n* [[Shooting at the 1976 Summer Paralympics|Shooting]]\n* [[Snooker at the 1976 Summer Paralympics|Snooker]]\n* [[Swimming at the 1976 Summer Paralympics|Swimming]]\n* [[Table tennis at the 1976 Summer Paralympics|Table tennis]]\n* [[Volleyball at the 1976 Summer Paralympics|Volleyball]]\n* [[Weightlifting at the 1976 Summer Paralympics|Weightlifting]]\n* [[Wheelchair basketball at the 1976 Summer Paralympics|Wheelchair basketball]]\n* [[Wheelchair fencing at the 1976 Summer Paralympics|Wheelchair fencing]]\n\n== Medal table ==\n{{Main|1976 Summer Paralympics medal table}}\nThe top 10 [[National Paralympic Committee|NPCs]] by number of gold medals are listed below. The host nation, Canada, is highlighted.\n{{Medals table\n | caption        = \n | host           = \n | flag_template  = FlagIPC\n | event          = 1976 Summer\n | team           = \n | gold_USA = 66 | silver_USA = 44 | bronze_USA = 45\n | gold_NED = 45 | silver_NED = 25 | bronze_NED = 14\n | gold_ISR = 40 | silver_ISR = 13 | bronze_ISR = 16\n | gold_FRG = 37 | silver_FRG = 34 | bronze_FRG = 26\n | gold_GBR = 29 | silver_GBR = 29 | bronze_GBR = 36\n | gold_CAN = 25 | silver_CAN = 26 | bronze_CAN = 26 | host_CAN = yes \n | gold_POL = 24 | silver_POL = 17 | bronze_POL = 12\n | gold_FRA = 23 | silver_FRA = 21 | bronze_FRA = 14\n | gold_SWE = 22 | silver_SWE = 27 | bronze_SWE = 24\n | gold_AUT = 17 | silver_AUT = 16 | bronze_AUT = 17\n}}\n\n== Participating delegations ==\nForty-one delegations took part in the Toronto Paralympics. [[Burma at the 1976 Summer Paralympics|Burma]], [[Colombia at the 1976 Summer Paralympics|Colombia]], [[Ecuador at the 1976 Summer Paralympics|Ecuador]], [[Greece at the 1976 Summer Paralympics|Greece]], [[Guatemala at the 1976 Summer Paralympics|Guatemala]], [[Indonesia at the 1976 Summer Paralympics|Indonesia]] and [[Luxembourg at the 1976 Summer Paralympics|Luxembourg]] made their first appearances.<ref>{{cite web |title= Medal Standings \u2013 Toronto 1976 Paralympic Games |publisher=[[International Paralympic Committee]] |year=2008 |url=http://www.paralympic.org/Sport/Results/reports.html?type=medalstandings&games=1976PG&sport=all |accessdate=2008-08-08}}</ref>\n\n[[South Africa at the Paralympics|South Africa]] was competing at the Paralympics for the fourth time. Although banned from the Olympic Games due to its policy of [[apartheid]], it was not banned from the Paralympics until 1980, and Canada, as host country, did not object to its participation. These were, however, to be its last Paralympics before the dismantling of apartheid; The [[Netherlands]], as hosts of the [[1980 Summer Paralympics|1980 Games]], declared South Africa's further participation \"undesirable\".<ref>[http://www.iisg.nl/collections/anti-apartheid/history/jaren70-5.php \"'The Netherlands against Apartheid' \u2013 1970s\"], International Institute of Social History</ref><ref>[http://www.paralympic.org/Sport/Results/search.html?npc=RSA&gender=all&medal=all&sport=all&games=all South Africa at the Paralympics], [[International Paralympic Committee]]</ref>\n{{clear}}\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-3}}\n* {{FlagIPC|ARG|1976 Summer|20}}\n* {{FlagIPC|AUS|1976 Summer|46}}\n* {{FlagIPC|AUT|1976 Summer|42}}\n* {{FlagIPC|BAH|1976 Summer|6}}\n* {{FlagIPC|BEL|1976 Summer|45}}\n* {{FlagIPC|BRA|1976 Summer|23}}\n* {{FlagIPC|BIR|1976 Summer|4}}\n* {{FlagIPC|CAN|1976 Summer|89}}\n* {{FlagIPC|COL|1976 Summer|11}}\n* {{FlagIPC|DEN|1976 Summer|21}}\n* {{FlagIPC|ECU|1976 Summer|3}}\n* {{FlagIPC|EGY|1976 Summer|27}}\n* {{FlagIPC|ETH|1976 Summer|1}}\n* {{FlagIPC|FIJ|1976 Summer|9}}\n{{Col-3}}\n* {{FlagIPC|FIN|1976 Summer|50}}\n* {{FlagIPC|FRA|1976 Summer|52}}\n* {{FlagIPC|GBR|1976 Summer|87}}\n* {{FlagIPC|GRE|1976 Summer|3}}\n* {{FlagIPC|GUA|1976 Summer|11}}\n* {{FlagIPC|HKG|1976 Summer|11}}\n* {{FlagIPC|HUN|1976 Summer|2}} \n* {{FlagIPC|INA|1976 Summer|12}}\n* {{FlagIPC|IRL|1976 Summer|19}}\n* {{FlagIPC|ISR|1976 Summer|59}}\n* {{FlagIPC|ITA|1976 Summer|24}}\n* {{FlagIPC|JPN|1976 Summer|34}}\n* {{FlagIPC|LUX|1976 Summer|3}}\n* {{FlagIPC|MEX|1976 Summer|32}}\n{{Col-3}}\n* {{FlagIPC|NED|1976 Summer|58}}\n* {{FlagIPC|NZL|1976 Summer|12}}\n* {{FlagIPC|NOR|1976 Summer|41}}\n* {{FlagIPC|PER|1976 Summer|2}}\n* {{FlagIPC|POL|1976 Summer|37}}\n* {{FlagIPC|RSA|1976 Summer|37}}\n* {{FlagIPC|KOR|1976 Summer|7}}\n* {{FlagIPC|ESP|1976 Summer|22}}\n* {{FlagIPC|SWE|1976 Summer|69}}\n* {{FlagIPC|SUI|1976 Summer|49}}\n* {{FlagIPC|UGA|1976 Summer|1}}\n* {{FlagIPC|USA|1976 Summer|97}}\n* {{FlagIPC|FRG|1976 Summer|93}}\n{{Col-end}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Sports}}\n* [[Canada at the Paralympics]]\n* World Paralympiads in Canada\n** 1976 Summer Paralympics \u2013 [[Toronto]]\n** [[2010 Winter Paralympics]] \u2013 [[Vancouver]]\u2014[[Whistler, British Columbia|Whistler]]\n* [[1976 Winter Paralympics]]\n* [[1976 Summer Olympics]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box\n| title = ''[[Summer Paralympic Games|Summer Paralympics]]'' <br />[[Toronto]]\n| before = [[1972 Summer Paralympics|Heidelberg]]\n| after = [[1980 Summer Paralympics|Arnhem]]\n| years = ''V Paralympic Summer Games'' (1976)\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Paralympic Games}}\n\n[[Category:1976 Summer Olympics|Paralympic]]\n[[Category:1976 in Canadian sports|Paralympics, 1976]]\n[[Category:1976 Summer Paralympics|*]]\n[[Category:International sports competitions hosted by Canada|Paralympics]]\n[[Category:1970s in Toronto]]\n[[Category:Multi-sport events in Canada]]\n[[Category:1976 in multi-sport events|Paralympic Games]]\n[[Category:Summer Paralympic Games]]\n[[Category:1976 in Ontario|Paralympic Games]]\n[[Category:August 1976 sports events in Canada]]\n[[Category:International sports competitions in Toronto]]\n", "name_user": "KingSkyLord", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1976_Summer_Paralympics"}
{"title_page": "Sreyash Sarkar", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name               = Sreyash Sarkar\n| image              = Sreyash_Sarkar.jpg\n| native_name        = \u09b6\u09cd\u09b0\u09c7\u09af\u09bc\u09b8 \u09b8\u09b0\u0995\u09be\u09b0\n| native_name_lang   = bn\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1993|09|20}}\n| birth_place        = [[Kolkata]], India\n| nationality        = Indian\n| occupation         = Poet, Musical Artist, Painter \n| genre              = Didactic Poetry\n| alma_mater         = [[South Point School]],<br>[[ESIEE Paris]],([[Ph.D.]]) \n| years_active       = 2013\u2013present\n| doctoral_advisor   = Tarik Bourouina, Philippe Basset\n| website            = {{URL|sreysarkar.weebly.com}}\n| signature = \n}}\n'''Sreyash Sarkar''' is an Indian [[Bengali people|Bengali]] poet and musical artist ([[Bengali language|Bengali]]:\u09b6\u09cd\u09b0\u09c7\u09af\u09bc\u09b8 \u09b8\u09b0\u0995\u09be\u09b0; born 20 September 1993).<ref name=\"Poet of the Month\">{{cite web | url=http://educationworld.co/Magazines/EWIssueSection.aspx?Issue=December_2014&Section=Young_Achievers | title= EducationWorld| publisher=Education World Magazine |year=2014 | accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"From a Hundred and Sixty Three Bengali Intellectuals\">{{cite web | url=http://indianculturalforum.in/2015/10/15/from-a-hundred/| title= Indian Cultural Forum|publisher=Indian Cultural Forum |year=2015 | accessdate=15 November 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"News from Africa\">{{cite web | url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181217063554/https://news.africa/2017/10/page/497/| title= News Africa| publisher= Le Mauricien |year=2017 | accessdate=16 October 2017}}</ref> Sarkar has been published in international literary journals<ref name=\"Author bio-The Legendary\">{{cite web | url=http://www.downdirtyword.com/authors/sreyashsarkar.html | title= The Legendary| publisher=The Legendary |year=2014 | accessdate=20 August 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Indigo Rising Magazine\">{{cite web | url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=t2zjBgAAQBAJ&pg=PT42&dq=%22Sreyash+Sarkar%22+-wikipedia&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjow-qCtaffAhUvqIsKHbhwCW0Q6AEIKjAA#v=onepage&q=%22Sreyash%20Sarkar%22%20-wikipedia&f=false| title= Indigo Rising Magazine| publisher=Indigo Rising Magazine |year=2015 | accessdate= 12 July 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Author bio-Galway Review Magazine\">{{cite web | url=https://thegalwayreview.com/2015/08/06/sreyash-sarkar-four-poems/ | title= Galway Review Magazine| publisher= Galway Review Magazine |year=2015 | accessdate= 2 July 2015}}</ref> and has been featured as the youngest polymath in [[Education World Magazine]]<ref name=\"Young Achievers\">{{cite web | url=http://educationworld.co/Magazines/EWIssueSection.aspx?Issue=December_2014&Section=Young_Achievers | title=Young Achievers | publisher=Education World Magazine |year=2014 | accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref> and in the French world magazine, [[Le Mauricien]]<ref name=\"Le Mauritien\">{{cite web | url=https://news.africa/2017/10/page/497/| title= Le Mauricien| publisher= Le Mauricien |year=2017 | accessdate=16 October 2017}}</ref> among others.\n\n== Early life ==\n\nBorn to noted physicist professor of the [[University of Calcutta]], Samir Kr. Sarkar and Pushpita Sarkar, a professor of Political Science at [[Bangabasi College]],<ref name=\"Poet of the Month\"/> Sarkar grew up in [[Calcutta]], India and studied at [[South Point School (India)|South Point School]].<ref name=\"South Point High School\">{{cite web | url=http://www.southpoint.edu.in/ArchiveAnnouncement.aspx?PageIndex=117&RecordPerPage=5| title= South Point High School| publisher= South Point High School |year=2012 | accessdate= 15 November 2012}}</ref> From his school-life onwards, he was a student correspondent for Voices, the literary supplement of [[The Statesman (India)|The Statesman]], [[Calcutta]], India. He received his initial musical training from his mother and later in [[Hindustani Classical Music]] in the [[Kirana gharana|Kirana]] and [[Gwalior gharana|Gwalior]] [[gharanas]], from Bidhan Chakrabarty, Rajyasree Ghosh, Sandip Ghosh, a disciple of Pt. [[A. Kanan]] and from Pt. Keerti Kumar Badsheshi, a disciple of Pt. [[Vinayak Torvi]]. His maternal [[grandaunt]] is the noted [[Hindustani Classical]] vocalist [[Padmashri]] Vidushi [[Sumitra Guha]].<ref name=\"Education World Online\">{{cite web | url=http://educationworld.co/Magazines/EWIssueSection.aspx?Issue=December_2014&Section=Young_Achievers | title= Young Achievers| publisher=Education World Magazine |year=2014 | accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref> He obtained his bachelor degree in Electrical and Electronic Engineering, from [[Visvesvaraya Technological University]], Karnataka. He later on, moved to Paris, France to pursue his post graduate studies for his [[diplome d'ingenieur]] in [[Microelectronics]] and [[Nanotechnology]] at [[ESIEE Paris]],where from he graduated in 2018 with top honours: ''mention tr\u00e8s bien avec les f\u00e9licitations du jury''<ref name=\"ESIEE Paris:C\u00c9R\u00c9MONIE DE REMISE DES DIPL\u00d4MES 2018\">{{cite web | url=https://www.esiee.fr/fr/actualite/ceremonie-remise-de-diplomes-2018| title=ESIEE Paris:C\u00c9R\u00c9MONIE DE REMISE DES DIPL\u00d4MES 2018 | publisher= ESIEE Paris |year=2018 | accessdate=26 December 2018}}</ref> and is presently pursuing his PhD on [[Metamaterials]].<ref name=\"Nouveau Album\">{{cite web | url=http://www.esiee.fr/fr/actualite/interview-sreyash-futur-ingenieur-mais-aussi-artiste| title= INTERVIEW \u2013 SREYASH, FUTUR ING\u00c9NIEUR MAIS AUSSI ARTISTE| publisher= ESIEE Paris |year=2018 | accessdate= 4 May 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Google Scholar-Articles\">{{cite web | url=https://scholar.google.fr/citations?user=Grxt-XwAAAAJ&hl=en#d=gs_md_cita-d&p=&u=%2Fcitations%3Fview_op%3Dview_citation%26hl%3Den%26user%3DGrxt-XwAAAAJ%26citation_for_view%3DGrxt-XwAAAAJ%3Au-x6o8ySG0sC%26tzom%3D-120| title= Publications| publisher= Google Scholar |year=2018 | accessdate= 4 May 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Researchgate-Articles\">{{cite web | url=https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Sreyash_Sarkar| title= Researcher Profile| publisher= Researchgate |year=2018 | accessdate= 4 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\nNotable poems written by Sarkar are listed at Eye on Life Magazine<ref name=\"Eye on Life Magazine\">{{cite web | url=https://eyeonlifemagazine.com/the-poetry-locksmith/sreyash-sarkar| title= Poetry Locksmith- Sreyash Sarkar| publisher=Eye on Life Magazine |year=2015 | accessdate= 20 December 2018}}</ref> and include:\n*''Whirligig''<ref>{{cite web |  url=https://eyeonlifemagazine.com/poetry-unlocked/whirligig|title=Whirligig| publisher=UReCA | date= 20 November 2015 | accessdate= 20 December 2018}}</ref>\n*''The Optical Symphony''<ref>{{cite web |  url=https://eyeonlifemagazine.com/poetry-unlocked/the-optical-symphony|title=The Optical Symphony| publisher=UReCA | date= 20 November 2015 | accessdate= 20 December 2018}}</ref> \n*''The Cage''\n*''The Macrame of Carnal Waves''\n*''I'm 23 and I'm Wearing a White Kurta''<ref name=\"I'm 23 and I'm Wearing a White Kurta a\">{{cite web | url=http://www.indianavoicejournal.com/2017/09/a-poem-by-sreyash-sarkar-im-23-and.html|title= Sreyash Sarkar| work= Indiana Voice Journal|year=2017 | accessdate=13 September 2017}}</ref>\n*''A Tibetan Epistle''<ref name=\"The Write Place at the Write Time a\">{{cite web | url= http://www.thewriteplaceatthewritetime.org/poetry.html| title= Sreyash Sarkar|publisher=The Write Place at the Write Time |year=2016 | accessdate=15 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Style==\nSarkar's works, as reviewed in The Galway Review<ref name=\"Sreyash Sarkar-Galway Review Magazine\">{{cite web | url=https://thegalwayreview.com/2015/08/06/sreyash-sarkar-four-poems/ | title= Galway Review Magazine, Sreyash Sarkar| publisher= Galway Review Magazine |year=2015 | accessdate= 2 July 2015}}</ref> and Red River Review, represents an endearing world of 'some basic formal truths'.\n\n[[Le Mauricien]] goes on to comment that, \n{{block quote|Sarkar thus delimits a position apart in the debate on the question of representation and brings up 'some basic formal truths' in pictorial space. The reflexive space, the powerful creations are not synonymous with anarchy. It is about safeguarding the autonomy of artistic creation and affirming a critical attitude towards the present world. Sarkar seems to question all objectivity in art, to approach the work as such, the expression of a search.[In his works] We see the misuse of motives, a short prosodic structure, a dry recitative and a rhythmic pattern constitutive of an intimate rumination, the effect of distancing and the search for an intimate cohesion.<ref name=\"News from Africa\">{{cite web | url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181217063554/https://news.africa/2017/10/page/497/| title= News Africa| publisher= Le Mauricien |year=2017 | accessdate=16 October 2017}}</ref>}}\nIn an interview for Arty Legume, he had indicated his principal poetic influences to be [[Rabindranath Tagore]], [[Rainer Maria Rilke]], [[Arthur Rimbaud]] & [[Sylvia Plath]], who taught him, poetic restraint and the 'economy of balance'.\n\nSarkar refuses to be labelled as an artist and remarks that 'there is an inherent difference between craftsmanship and artistry' and instead prefers to be called a 'technician, who picks up the pen or brush to accomplish the job. Whether the end result is art, is unknown [to him]'.<ref name=\"Interview for Inkscape Magazine\">>{{cite web | url=https://sreysarkar.weebly.com/| title= Interview for Inkscape Magazine| work= Inkscape Magazine |year=2017 | accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\nPublications containing Sarkar's works are listed as:\n\nEnglish\n* Five Poetry Magazine \n* [[Literal Latte]]\n* [[B O D Y]]\n* UReCA<ref name=\"UReCA\">{{cite web | url=http://www.nchc-ureca.com/on-the-pastures-of-pursuit.html|title=On the Pastures of Pursuit| publisher=UReCA |year=2018 | accessdate= 5 November 2018}}</ref>\n* Southlit Literary Journal<ref name=\"SouthLit\">{{cite web | url=https://www.southlit.org/southlit-september-2014/southlit-september-2014-content|title= Sreyash Sarkar| publisher= SouthLit|year=2014 | accessdate=5 September 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Indiana Review]]<ref name=\"I'm 23 and I'm Wearing a White Kurta a\"/>\n* Ember<ref name=\"Ember\">{{cite web | url= https://www.indiegogo.com/projects/ember-a-journal-of-luminous-things#/|title= Sreyash Sarkar| publisher= Ember|year=2014 | accessdate=15 March 2017}}</ref>\n* Red River Review<ref name=\"Red River Review\">{{cite web | url= http://www.redriverreview.net/A55656/rrr.nsf/7684f5ba6525b72485257d1b001adadf/bcece4a88a669bbd85257d1b001ac069?OpenDocument/|title= Sreyash Sarkar| publisher= Red River Review|year=2013 | accessdate=15 March 2013}}</ref>\n* The Eastern New Mexico University's Art & Crafts journal, El Portal, list including ''Whirligig'' by Sarkar<ref name=\"El Portal\">{{cite web | url= https://elportaljournal.com/2015/11/13/el-portal-fall-2015-edition/|title= Sreyash Sarkar| publisher= El Portal|year=2015 | accessdate=15 May 2015}}</ref>\n* Circus Book<ref name=\"Circus Book\">{{cite web | url= https://circusbook.org/author/sreyashsarkar/|title= Sreyash Sarkar|  publisher= Circus Book|year=2015 | accessdate=15 May 2015}}</ref>\n* Ijagun Poetry Journal<ref name=\"Ijagun Poetry Journal\">{{cite web | url= https://ijagunpoetryjournal.com/tag/sreyash-sarkar/|title= Sreyash Sarkar| work= Ijagun Poetry Journal|year=2014 | accessdate=7 March 2014}}</ref>\n* Pif Magazine<ref name=\"Pif Magazine\">{{cite web | url= http://www.pifmagazine.com/2016/02/the-optical-symphony/| title= Sreyash Sarkar|work= Pif magazine|year=2016 | accessdate=15 May 2016}}</ref>\n* [[The Write Place at the Write Time]]<ref name=\"The Write Place at the Write Time a\"/>\n* Scarlet Leaf Review Magazine<ref name=\"Scarlet Leaf Review\">{{cite web | url= https://www.scarletleafreview.com/poems7/category/sreyash-sarkar| title= Sreyash Sarkar|publisher=Scarlet Leaf Review|year=2017 | accessdate=15 May 2017}}</ref>\n* [[The Legendary]]<ref name=\"Author bio-The Legendary\"/>\n* Indigo Rising Magazine<ref name=\"Author bio:Indigo Rising Magazine\">{{cite web | url=http://www.indigorisingmagazine.com/2015/03/irm-vol-2-issue-1.html | title= Indigo Rising Magazine| publisher=Indigo Rising Magazine |year=2015 | accessdate= 12 July 2015}}</ref>\n* Galway Review Magazine<ref name=\"Author bio-Galway Review Magazine\"/>\n* Cecile's Writers Magazine<ref name=\"Cecile's Writers Magazine\">{{cite web | url=http://www.cecileswriters.com/mag/story/lyrics-for-magnolia-too/|title=Cecile's Writers Magazine| publisher=Cecile's Writers Magazine|year=2018 | accessdate= 2 July 2018}}</ref>\n* Creativica<ref name=\"Creativica\">{{cite web | url=https://www.creativica.in/lyrics-for-magnolia-too/|title=Creativica| publisher=Creativica|year=2018 | accessdate= 2 July 2018}}</ref>\n* Poetry Pacific<ref name=\"Poetry Pacific\">{{cite web | url=http://poetrypacific.blogspot.com/2014/11/1-poem-by-sreyash-sarkar.html| title= 1 Poem by Sreyash Sarkar| publisher= Poetry Pacific|year=2014 | accessdate= 5 November 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Tin House]]\n* River River Journal<ref name=\"River River Journal\">{{cite web | url=http://riverriver.org/issues/nine/im-23-and-im-wearing-a-white-kurta/|title=River River| publisher=River River|year=2019 | accessdate= 2 July 2019}}</ref>\n* Poetry Pacific<ref name=\"Poetry Pacific\"/>\n* [[Plainsongs]], Literary journal of Hastings College Press\n* The Cape Rock, Southeast Missouri State University Press\n* [[Fifth Wednesday Journal]]\n* Fowl Feathered Review\n* Dumas Demain\n* Griffel<ref name=\"How Late Was I, Ciudad?\">>{{cite web | url=https://www.griffel.no/article/how-late-was-i-ciudad/|title=Griffel| work=Griffel Journal|year=2020 | accessdate= 2 January 2020}}</ref>\n* The Paragon Journal<ref name=\"Paragon Journal\">{{cite web | url=https://www.theparagonjournal.com/current-issue|title= The Paragon Journal| work=Paragon Journal|year=2018 | accessdate= 2 July 2018}}</ref>\n* Leaves of Ink<ref name=\"Leaves of Ink\">{{cite web | url=http://www.leaves-of-ink.com/search/?q=sreyash+sarkar|title= Leaves of Ink| publisher=Leaves of Ink|year=2017 | accessdate= 24 October 2017}}</ref>\n* TreeHouse Arts<ref name=\"TreeHouse Arts\">{{cite web | url=https://treehousearts.me/2014/06/24/the-cage-by-sreyash-sarkar/|title= TreeHouse Arts| publisher=TreeHouse Arts|year=2015 | accessdate= 24 October 2015}}</ref>\n* The Bitchin' Kitsch<ref name=\"The Bitchin' Kitsch\">{{cite web | url=http://www.talbot-heindl.com/aug2014|title= The Bitchin' Kitsch| publisher=The Bitchin' Kitsch|year=2014 | accessdate= 24 August 2014}}</ref>\n* The Non-Functioning Scribblers<ref name=\"The Non-fuctionning Scribblers\">{{cite web|url=https://treehousearts.me/2014/06/24/the-cage-by-sreyash-sarkar/|title= TreeHouse Arts|publisher=The Non-fuctionning Scribblers|year=2016 }}</ref>\n[[Bengali language|Bengali]]\n* [[Anandabazar Patrika]]<ref name=\"ABP- Lekha 1\">{{cite web | url= https://www.anandabazar.com/international/french-songs-with-football-fever-1.829229?ref=international-new-stry| title= Football & France, Sreyash Sarkar|publisher=ABP|year=2018 | accessdate=8 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"ABP- Lekha 2\">{{cite web | url= https://www.anandabazar.com/international/france-celebrates-win-over-belgium-1.830943?ref=international-new-stry| title=France Celebrates, Sreyash Sarkar|publisher=ABP|year=2018 | accessdate=8 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"ABP- Lekha 3\">{{cite web | url= https://www.anandabazar.com/international/local-resident-shares-his-experience-over-fuel-tax-protest-in-paris-1.909070| title=Fuel Tax Protests in France, Sreyash Sarkar|publisher=ABP|year=2018 | accessdate=8 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"ABP- Lekha 4\">{{cite web | url= https://www.anandabazar.com/international/coronavirus-people-of-france-didn-t-stop-to-kissing-each-other-1.1129168?fbclid=IwAR1_lkdDDjuGRvUxN5u84yk9aH_e0GlIRbXIgGE1I75jni2yWvWbYgPMWmQ| title= CoronaVirus in France, Sreyash Sarkar|publisher=ABP|year=2020 | accessdate=30 March  2020}}</ref>\n* Adorer Nauka<ref name=\"Adorer Nauka- Kobita 1\">{{cite web | url= http://www.aadorernouka.in/adorernauka/Article/646/%E0%A6%B6%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%B0%E0%A7%87%E0%A7%9F%E0%A6%B8%20%E0%A6%B8%E0%A6%B0%E0%A6%95%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%B0%20%20%E0%A6%97%E0%A6%AC%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%95%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%B7%E0%A6%AA%E0%A6%A5%E0%A7%87.html| title= Sreyash Sarkar|publisher=Adorer Nauka- Kobita |year=2016 | accessdate=15 May 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Adorer Nauka- Kobita 2 \">{{cite web | url= http://www.aadorernouka.in/adorernauka/Article/518/%E0%A6%B6%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%B0%E0%A7%87%E0%A7%9F%E0%A6%B8%20%E0%A6%B8%E0%A6%B0%E0%A6%95%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%B0%20%20%E0%A6%95%E0%A7%8B%E0%A6%B2%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%B9%E0%A6%B2%20.html| title= Sreyash Sarkar|publisher=Adorer Nauka- Kobita |year=2016 | accessdate=15 May 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Adorer Nauka - Rituparno Ghosh\">{{cite web | url= http://www.aadorernouka.in/adorernauka/Article/430/%E0%A6%B6%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%B0%E0%A7%87%E0%A7%9F%E0%A6%B8%20%E0%A6%B8%E0%A6%B0%E0%A6%95%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%B0%20%20%20%E0%A6%85%E0%A6%B2%E0%A6%95%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%A4%E0%A6%95%E0%A7%87%E0%A6%B0%20%E0%A6%A6%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%97%20%E0%A6%93%20%E0%A6%AC%E0%A7%88%E0%A6%B6%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%96%E0%A7%80%20%E0%A6%B0%E0%A7%8B%E0%A6%A6%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%A6%E0%A7%81%E0%A6%B0%20.html| title= Sreyash Sarkar|publisher=Adorer Nauka- Kobita |year=2016 | accessdate=15 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Music ==\nThough Sarkar has been trained in [[Hindustani Classical Music]] and [[Rabindrasangeet]], his published music albums are of crossover Western Classical genre. In 2017, [[Universal Records]] released his first single 'July' and then another single titled 'Simple Songs'<ref name=\"Nouveau Album 2\">{{cite web | url=http://www.esiee.fr/fr/actualite/interview-sreyash-futur-ingenieur-mais-aussi-artiste| title= INTERVIEW \u2013 SREYASH, FUTUR ING\u00c9NIEUR MAIS AUSSI ARTISTE| publisher= ESIEE Paris |year=2018 | accessdate= 4 May 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Nouveau Album 6\">{{cite web | url=[https://open.spotify.com/album/1DlMX4Fr9njBTb01VZaUaj Sreyash Sarkar's album Simple Songs on Spotify]\n| title= INTERVIEW \u2013 SREYASH, FUTUR ING\u00c9NIEUR MAIS AUSSI ARTISTE| publisher= ESIEE Paris |year=2018 | accessdate= 4 May 2018}}</ref>     came out in  comprising of three compositions in piano, clarinet and combining other atmospheric sounds.<ref name=\"Nouveau Album 1\">{{cite web | url=http://www.esiee.fr/fr/actualite/interview-sreyash-futur-ingenieur-mais-aussi-artiste| title= INTERVIEW \u2013 SREYASH, FUTUR ING\u00c9NIEUR MAIS AUSSI ARTISTE| publisher= ESIEE Paris |year=2018 | accessdate= 4 May 2018}}</ref>  \nIn an article reviewing [[Ludovico Einaudi]]'s album Elements<ref name=\"The Non-fuctionning Scribblers 1\">{{cite web|url=https://treehousearts.me/2014/06/24/the-cage-by-sreyash-sarkar/|title= TreeHouse Arts|publisher=The Non-fuctionning Scribblers|year=2016 }}</ref><ref name=\"The Non-fuctionning Scribblers 2\">{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190624123803/http://www.thenonfunctioningscribblers.com/user/sreyash-sarkar|title= TreeHouse Arts|publisher=The Non-fuctionning Scribblers|year=2016 }}</ref>, Sarkar notes his understanding of music as a 'series of repetitions woven into absolute, simplicity of silence'. \nAndy Fischer of Score magazine reviewed Sarkar's Simple Songs, taking note of this 'relentless pursuit for the nature of simplicity'.     \n\n\n== Engineering award ==\n* Best Poster Award, THERMINIC 2019, Lecco Italy.<ref name=\"Therminic 2019\">{{cite web | url=https://therminic2019.eu/ | title= Young Achievers| publisher=Therminic 2019 |year=2019 | accessdate=15 November 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"ESIEE NEWS 2019\">{{cite web | url=https://www.esiee.fr/fr/actualite/recherche/prix-doctorant-esiee-therminic-2019 | title= Young Achievers| publisher=ESIEE 2019 |year=2019 | accessdate=20 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://riverriver.org/issues/nine/im-23-and-im-wearing-a-white-kurta/ ''I'm 23 and I'm Wearing a White Kurta'' by Sreyash Sarkar on Issue 9, River River Magazine.]\n* [http://sreysarkar.weebly.com Official website]\n* [https://www.facebook.com/SreyashSarkarofficial/ Facebook Profile]\n* [https://www.instagram.com/sreyashsarkar/ Instagram Profile]\n* [https://www.facebook.com/SreyashSarkarofficial/videos/1003545406646033/ Interview with Sreyash Sarkar in ''Inkspace Magazine'' (English)]\n* [https://music.apple.com/in/artist/sreyash-sarkar/1289085658 Sreyash Sarkar on Apple Music]\n* [https://open.spotify.com/album/1DlMX4Fr9njBTb01VZaUaj Sreyash Sarkar's album Simple Songs on Spotify]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sarkar, Sreyash}}\n[[Category:1993 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Bengali male poets]]\n[[Category:Indian male poets]]\n[[Category:Poets from West Bengal]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name               = Sreyash Sarkar\n| image              = Sreyash_Sarkar.jpg\n| native_name        = \u09b6\u09cd\u09b0\u09c7\u09af\u09bc\u09b8 \u09b8\u09b0\u0995\u09be\u09b0\n| native_name_lang   = bn\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1993|09|20}}\n| birth_place        = [[Kolkata]], India\n| nationality        = Indian\n| occupation         = Poet, Musical Artist, Painter \n| genre              = Didactic Poetry\n| alma_mater         = [[South Point School]],<br>[[ESIEE Paris]],([[Ph.D.]]) \n| years_active       = 2013\u2013present\n| doctoral_advisor   = Tarik Bourouina, Philippe Basset\n| website            = {{URL|sreysarkar.weebly.com}}\n| signature = \n}}\n'''Sreyash Sarkar''' is an Indian [[Bengali people|Bengali]] poet and musical artist ([[Bengali language|Bengali]]:\u09b6\u09cd\u09b0\u09c7\u09af\u09bc\u09b8 \u09b8\u09b0\u0995\u09be\u09b0; born 20 September 1993).<ref name=\"Poet of the Month\">{{cite web | url=http://educationworld.co/Magazines/EWIssueSection.aspx?Issue=December_2014&Section=Young_Achievers | title= EducationWorld| publisher=Education World Magazine |year=2014 | accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"From a Hundred and Sixty Three Bengali Intellectuals\">{{cite web | url=http://indianculturalforum.in/2015/10/15/from-a-hundred/| title= Indian Cultural Forum|publisher=Indian Cultural Forum |year=2015 | accessdate=15 November 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"News from Africa\">{{cite web | url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181217063554/https://news.africa/2017/10/page/497/| title= News Africa| publisher= Le Mauricien |year=2017 | accessdate=16 October 2017}}</ref> Sarkar has been published in international literary journals<ref name=\"Author bio-The Legendary\">{{cite web | url=http://www.downdirtyword.com/authors/sreyashsarkar.html | title= The Legendary| publisher=The Legendary |year=2014 | accessdate=20 August 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Indigo Rising Magazine\">{{cite web | url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=t2zjBgAAQBAJ&pg=PT42&dq=%22Sreyash+Sarkar%22+-wikipedia&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjow-qCtaffAhUvqIsKHbhwCW0Q6AEIKjAA#v=onepage&q=%22Sreyash%20Sarkar%22%20-wikipedia&f=false| title= Indigo Rising Magazine| publisher=Indigo Rising Magazine |year=2015 | accessdate= 12 July 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Author bio-Galway Review Magazine\">{{cite web | url=https://thegalwayreview.com/2015/08/06/sreyash-sarkar-four-poems/ | title= Galway Review Magazine| publisher= Galway Review Magazine |year=2015 | accessdate= 2 July 2015}}</ref> and has been featured as the youngest polymath in [[Education World Magazine]]<ref name=\"Young Achievers\">{{cite web | url=http://educationworld.co/Magazines/EWIssueSection.aspx?Issue=December_2014&Section=Young_Achievers | title=Young Achievers | publisher=Education World Magazine |year=2014 | accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref> and in the French world magazine, [[Le Mauricien]]<ref name=\"Le Mauritien\">{{cite web | url=https://news.africa/2017/10/page/497/| title= Le Mauricien| publisher= Le Mauricien |year=2017 | accessdate=16 October 2017}}</ref> among others.\n\n== Early life ==\n\nBorn to noted physicist professor of the [[University of Calcutta]], Samir Kr. Sarkar and Pushpita Sarkar, a professor of Political Science at [[Bangabasi College]],<ref name=\"Poet of the Month\"/> Sarkar grew up in [[Calcutta]], India and studied at [[South Point School (India)|South Point School]].<ref name=\"South Point High School\">{{cite web | url=http://www.southpoint.edu.in/ArchiveAnnouncement.aspx?PageIndex=117&RecordPerPage=5| title= South Point High School| publisher= South Point High School |year=2012 | accessdate= 15 November 2012}}</ref> From his school-life onwards, he was a student correspondent for Voices, the literary supplement of [[The Statesman (India)|The Statesman]], [[Calcutta]], India. He received his initial musical training from his mother and later in [[Hindustani Classical Music]] in the [[Kirana gharana|Kirana]] and [[Gwalior gharana|Gwalior]] [[gharanas]], from Bidhan Chakrabarty, Rajyasree Ghosh, Sandip Ghosh, a disciple of Pt. [[A. Kanan]] and from Pt. Keerti Kumar Badsheshi, a disciple of Pt. [[Vinayak Torvi]]. His maternal [[grandaunt]] is the noted [[Hindustani Classical]] vocalist [[Padmashri]] Vidushi [[Sumitra Guha]].<ref name=\"Education World Online\">{{cite web | url=http://educationworld.co/Magazines/EWIssueSection.aspx?Issue=December_2014&Section=Young_Achievers | title= Young Achievers| publisher=Education World Magazine |year=2014 | accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref> He obtained his bachelor degree in Electrical and Electronic Engineering, from [[Visvesvaraya Technological University]], Karnataka. He later on, moved to Paris, France to pursue his post graduate studies for his [[diplome d'ingenieur]] in [[Microelectronics]] and [[Nanotechnology]] at [[ESIEE Paris]],where from he graduated in 2018 with top honours: ''mention tr\u00e8s bien avec les f\u00e9licitations du jury''<ref name=\"ESIEE Paris:C\u00c9R\u00c9MONIE DE REMISE DES DIPL\u00d4MES 2018\">{{cite web | url=https://www.esiee.fr/fr/actualite/ceremonie-remise-de-diplomes-2018| title=ESIEE Paris:C\u00c9R\u00c9MONIE DE REMISE DES DIPL\u00d4MES 2018 | publisher= ESIEE Paris |year=2018 | accessdate=26 December 2018}}</ref> and is presently pursuing his PhD on [[Metamaterials]].<ref name=\"Nouveau Album\">{{cite web | url=http://www.esiee.fr/fr/actualite/interview-sreyash-futur-ingenieur-mais-aussi-artiste| title= INTERVIEW \u2013 SREYASH, FUTUR ING\u00c9NIEUR MAIS AUSSI ARTISTE| publisher= ESIEE Paris |year=2018 | accessdate= 4 May 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Google Scholar-Articles\">{{cite web | url=https://scholar.google.fr/citations?user=Grxt-XwAAAAJ&hl=en#d=gs_md_cita-d&p=&u=%2Fcitations%3Fview_op%3Dview_citation%26hl%3Den%26user%3DGrxt-XwAAAAJ%26citation_for_view%3DGrxt-XwAAAAJ%3Au-x6o8ySG0sC%26tzom%3D-120| title= Publications| publisher= Google Scholar |year=2018 | accessdate= 4 May 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Researchgate-Articles\">{{cite web | url=https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Sreyash_Sarkar| title= Researcher Profile| publisher= Researchgate |year=2018 | accessdate= 4 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\nNotable poems written by Sarkar are listed at Eye on Life Magazine<ref name=\"Eye on Life Magazine\">{{cite web | url=https://eyeonlifemagazine.com/the-poetry-locksmith/sreyash-sarkar| title= Poetry Locksmith- Sreyash Sarkar| publisher=Eye on Life Magazine |year=2015 | accessdate= 20 December 2018}}</ref> and include:\n*''Whirligig''<ref>{{cite web |  url=https://eyeonlifemagazine.com/poetry-unlocked/whirligig|title=Whirligig| publisher=UReCA | date= 20 November 2015 | accessdate= 20 December 2018}}</ref>\n*''The Optical Symphony''<ref>{{cite web |  url=https://eyeonlifemagazine.com/poetry-unlocked/the-optical-symphony|title=The Optical Symphony| publisher=UReCA | date= 20 November 2015 | accessdate= 20 December 2018}}</ref> \n*''The Cage''\n*''The Macrame of Carnal Waves''\n*''I'm 23 and I'm Wearing a White Kurta''<ref name=\"I'm 23 and I'm Wearing a White Kurta a\">{{cite web | url=http://www.indianavoicejournal.com/2017/09/a-poem-by-sreyash-sarkar-im-23-and.html|title= Sreyash Sarkar| work= Indiana Voice Journal|year=2017 | accessdate=13 September 2017}}</ref>\n*''A Tibetan Epistle''<ref name=\"The Write Place at the Write Time a\">{{cite web | url= http://www.thewriteplaceatthewritetime.org/poetry.html| title= Sreyash Sarkar|publisher=The Write Place at the Write Time |year=2016 | accessdate=15 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Style==\nSarkar's works, as reviewed in The Galway Review<ref name=\"Sreyash Sarkar-Galway Review Magazine\">{{cite web | url=https://thegalwayreview.com/2015/08/06/sreyash-sarkar-four-poems/ | title= Galway Review Magazine, Sreyash Sarkar| publisher= Galway Review Magazine |year=2015 | accessdate= 2 July 2015}}</ref> and Red River Review, represents an endearing world of 'some basic formal truths'.\n\n[[Le Mauricien]] goes on to comment that, \n{{block quote|Sarkar thus delimits a position apart in the debate on the question of representation and brings up 'some basic formal truths' in pictorial space. The reflexive space, the powerful creations are not synonymous with anarchy. It is about safeguarding the autonomy of artistic creation and affirming a critical attitude towards the present world. Sarkar seems to question all objectivity in art, to approach the work as such, the expression of a search.[In his works] We see the misuse of motives, a short prosodic structure, a dry recitative and a rhythmic pattern constitutive of an intimate rumination, the effect of distancing and the search for an intimate cohesion.<ref name=\"News from Africa\">{{cite web | url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181217063554/https://news.africa/2017/10/page/497/| title= News Africa| publisher= Le Mauricien |year=2017 | accessdate=16 October 2017}}</ref>}}\nIn an interview for Arty Legume, he had indicated his principal poetic influences to be [[Rabindranath Tagore]], [[Rainer Maria Rilke]], [[Arthur Rimbaud]] & [[Sylvia Plath]], who taught him, poetic restraint and the 'economy of balance'.\n\nSarkar refuses to be labelled as an artist and remarks that 'there is an inherent difference between craftsmanship and artistry' and instead prefers to be called a 'technician, who picks up the pen or brush to accomplish the job. Whether the end result is art, is unknown [to him]'.<ref name=\"Interview for Inkscape Magazine\">>{{cite web | url=https://sreysarkar.weebly.com/| title= Interview for Inkscape Magazine| work= Inkscape Magazine |year=2017 | accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\nPublications containing Sarkar's works are listed as:\n\nEnglish\n* Five Poetry Magazine \n* [[Literal Latte]]\n* [[B O D Y]]\n* UReCA<ref name=\"UReCA\">{{cite web | url=http://www.nchc-ureca.com/on-the-pastures-of-pursuit.html|title=On the Pastures of Pursuit| publisher=UReCA |year=2018 | accessdate= 5 November 2018}}</ref>\n* Southlit Literary Journal<ref name=\"SouthLit\">{{cite web | url=https://www.southlit.org/southlit-september-2014/southlit-september-2014-content|title= Sreyash Sarkar| publisher= SouthLit|year=2014 | accessdate=5 September 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Indiana Review]]<ref name=\"I'm 23 and I'm Wearing a White Kurta a\"/>\n* Ember<ref name=\"Ember\">{{cite web | url= https://www.indiegogo.com/projects/ember-a-journal-of-luminous-things#/|title= Sreyash Sarkar| publisher= Ember|year=2014 | accessdate=15 March 2017}}</ref>\n* Red River Review<ref name=\"Red River Review\">{{cite web | url= http://www.redriverreview.net/A55656/rrr.nsf/7684f5ba6525b72485257d1b001adadf/bcece4a88a669bbd85257d1b001ac069?OpenDocument/|title= Sreyash Sarkar| publisher= Red River Review|year=2013 | accessdate=15 March 2013}}</ref>\n* The Eastern New Mexico University's Art & Crafts journal, El Portal, list including ''Whirligig'' by Sarkar<ref name=\"El Portal\">{{cite web | url= https://elportaljournal.com/2015/11/13/el-portal-fall-2015-edition/|title= Sreyash Sarkar| publisher= El Portal|year=2015 | accessdate=15 May 2015}}</ref>\n* Circus Book<ref name=\"Circus Book\">{{cite web | url= https://circusbook.org/author/sreyashsarkar/|title= Sreyash Sarkar|  publisher= Circus Book|year=2015 | accessdate=15 May 2015}}</ref>\n* Ijagun Poetry Journal<ref name=\"Ijagun Poetry Journal\">{{cite web | url= https://ijagunpoetryjournal.com/tag/sreyash-sarkar/|title= Sreyash Sarkar| work= Ijagun Poetry Journal|year=2014 | accessdate=7 March 2014}}</ref>\n* Pif Magazine<ref name=\"Pif Magazine\">{{cite web | url= http://www.pifmagazine.com/2016/02/the-optical-symphony/| title= Sreyash Sarkar|work= Pif magazine|year=2016 | accessdate=15 May 2016}}</ref>\n* [[The Write Place at the Write Time]]<ref name=\"The Write Place at the Write Time a\"/>\n* Scarlet Leaf Review Magazine<ref name=\"Scarlet Leaf Review\">{{cite web | url= https://www.scarletleafreview.com/poems7/category/sreyash-sarkar| title= Sreyash Sarkar|publisher=Scarlet Leaf Review|year=2017 | accessdate=15 May 2017}}</ref>\n* [[The Legendary]]<ref name=\"Author bio-The Legendary\"/>\n* Indigo Rising Magazine<ref name=\"Author bio:Indigo Rising Magazine\">{{cite web | url=http://www.indigorisingmagazine.com/2015/03/irm-vol-2-issue-1.html | title= Indigo Rising Magazine| publisher=Indigo Rising Magazine |year=2015 | accessdate= 12 July 2015}}</ref>\n* Galway Review Magazine<ref name=\"Author bio-Galway Review Magazine\"/>\n* Cecile's Writers Magazine<ref name=\"Cecile's Writers Magazine\">{{cite web | url=http://www.cecileswriters.com/mag/story/lyrics-for-magnolia-too/|title=Cecile's Writers Magazine| publisher=Cecile's Writers Magazine|year=2018 | accessdate= 2 July 2018}}</ref>\n* Creativica<ref name=\"Creativica\">{{cite web | url=https://www.creativica.in/lyrics-for-magnolia-too/|title=Creativica| publisher=Creativica|year=2018 | accessdate= 2 July 2018}}</ref>\n* Poetry Pacific<ref name=\"Poetry Pacific\">{{cite web | url=http://poetrypacific.blogspot.com/2014/11/1-poem-by-sreyash-sarkar.html| title= 1 Poem by Sreyash Sarkar| publisher= Poetry Pacific|year=2014 | accessdate= 5 November 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Tin House]]\n* River River Journal<ref name=\"River River Journal\">{{cite web | url=http://riverriver.org/issues/nine/im-23-and-im-wearing-a-white-kurta/|title=River River| publisher=River River|year=2019 | accessdate= 2 July 2019}}</ref>\n* Poetry Pacific<ref name=\"Poetry Pacific\"/>\n* [[Plainsongs]], Literary journal of Hastings College Press\n* The Cape Rock, Southeast Missouri State University Press\n* [[Fifth Wednesday Journal]]\n* Fowl Feathered Review\n* Dumas Demain\n* Griffel<ref name=\"How Late Was I, Ciudad?\">>{{cite web | url=https://www.griffel.no/article/how-late-was-i-ciudad/|title=Griffel| work=Griffel Journal|year=2020 | accessdate= 2 January 2020}}</ref>\n* The Paragon Journal<ref name=\"Paragon Journal\">{{cite web | url=https://www.theparagonjournal.com/current-issue|title= The Paragon Journal| work=Paragon Journal|year=2018 | accessdate= 2 July 2018}}</ref>\n* Leaves of Ink<ref name=\"Leaves of Ink\">{{cite web | url=http://www.leaves-of-ink.com/search/?q=sreyash+sarkar|title= Leaves of Ink| publisher=Leaves of Ink|year=2017 | accessdate= 24 October 2017}}</ref>\n* TreeHouse Arts<ref name=\"TreeHouse Arts\">{{cite web | url=https://treehousearts.me/2014/06/24/the-cage-by-sreyash-sarkar/|title= TreeHouse Arts| publisher=TreeHouse Arts|year=2015 | accessdate= 24 October 2015}}</ref>\n* The Bitchin' Kitsch<ref name=\"The Bitchin' Kitsch\">{{cite web | url=http://www.talbot-heindl.com/aug2014|title= The Bitchin' Kitsch| publisher=The Bitchin' Kitsch|year=2014 | accessdate= 24 August 2014}}</ref>\n* The Non-Functioning Scribblers<ref name=\"The Non-fuctionning Scribblers\">{{cite web|url=https://treehousearts.me/2014/06/24/the-cage-by-sreyash-sarkar/|title= TreeHouse Arts|publisher=The Non-fuctionning Scribblers|year=2016 }}</ref>\n[[Bengali language|Bengali]]\n* [[Anandabazar Patrika]]<ref name=\"ABP- Lekha 1\">{{cite web | url= https://www.anandabazar.com/international/french-songs-with-football-fever-1.829229?ref=international-new-stry| title= Football & France, Sreyash Sarkar|publisher=ABP|year=2018 | accessdate=8 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"ABP- Lekha 2\">{{cite web | url= https://www.anandabazar.com/international/france-celebrates-win-over-belgium-1.830943?ref=international-new-stry| title=France Celebrates, Sreyash Sarkar|publisher=ABP|year=2018 | accessdate=8 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"ABP- Lekha 3\">{{cite web | url= https://www.anandabazar.com/international/local-resident-shares-his-experience-over-fuel-tax-protest-in-paris-1.909070| title=Fuel Tax Protests in France, Sreyash Sarkar|publisher=ABP|year=2018 | accessdate=8 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"ABP- Lekha 4\">{{cite web | url= https://www.anandabazar.com/international/coronavirus-people-of-france-didn-t-stop-to-kissing-each-other-1.1129168?fbclid=IwAR1_lkdDDjuGRvUxN5u84yk9aH_e0GlIRbXIgGE1I75jni2yWvWbYgPMWmQ| title= CoronaVirus in France, Sreyash Sarkar|publisher=ABP|year=2020 | accessdate=30 March  2020}}</ref>\n* Adorer Nauka<ref name=\"Adorer Nauka- Kobita 1\">{{cite web | url= http://www.aadorernouka.in/adorernauka/Article/646/%E0%A6%B6%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%B0%E0%A7%87%E0%A7%9F%E0%A6%B8%20%E0%A6%B8%E0%A6%B0%E0%A6%95%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%B0%20%20%E0%A6%97%E0%A6%AC%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%95%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%B7%E0%A6%AA%E0%A6%A5%E0%A7%87.html| title= Sreyash Sarkar|publisher=Adorer Nauka- Kobita |year=2016 | accessdate=15 May 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Adorer Nauka- Kobita 2 \">{{cite web | url= http://www.aadorernouka.in/adorernauka/Article/518/%E0%A6%B6%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%B0%E0%A7%87%E0%A7%9F%E0%A6%B8%20%E0%A6%B8%E0%A6%B0%E0%A6%95%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%B0%20%20%E0%A6%95%E0%A7%8B%E0%A6%B2%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%B9%E0%A6%B2%20.html| title= Sreyash Sarkar|publisher=Adorer Nauka- Kobita |year=2016 | accessdate=15 May 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Adorer Nauka - Rituparno Ghosh\">{{cite web | url= http:/